Hello Samuel.

You wrote:
>> I was just wondering if there were any plans for making a PPC version of
>> blitz. It should not be that hard, recode the compiler to compile commands
>> for the PPC instead of 68k and maybe kernel selection (PowerUP/WarpOS).

> This is a great idea, i also wish this was possible - but this would mean
> either:

> a) Acid Software update Blitz to work on PPCs - but Acid Software no longer
> exists IIRC.
> b) Acid Software (or whoever the source is copyright to) release the source
> to the public for people to port it themselves
> c) Acid Software licence the porting of Blitz to PPC to another company.

Actually it would mean:

d) since a good portion of all Blitz "commands" are in EXTERNAL 680x0 assembly binaries (called libraries) you would have to re-compile your AMiGA specific 680x0 assembly to open, object oriented, superscalar PPC code, that can be run using either libraries.

I really wish you alot of luck. :o> I'm not saying it's impossible, but by the time you're done with it, no-one will be able to remember what a PPC is anymore :o>

On a second note, someone was once developing a PPC support library for Blitz, whatever happened to it, I dunno. But I was thinking, maybe you coould create  library (like say an add-on to the NCS) that could be run on the PPC, to do math intensive work, and 3D stuff. (Hold that thought for a second, and convert the Warp3D stuff aswell while you're at it.)


Greets,
-- 

