@NODE "Mail_81" "Re: Blitz PPC"
From: Anton Reinauer <anton@ww.co.nz>
Date: Wed, 23 Jun 1999 12:42:50 +1200
Subject: Re: Blitz PPC
Encoding: 8bit
X-UIDL: 9b8e032a5d398fb24845e83d726119ee

On 21-Jun-99, Mikkel Lřkke wrote:
 
>>> I was just wondering if there were any plans for making a PPC
>>> version of blitz. It should not be that hard, recode the compiler to
>>> compile commands for the PPC instead of 68k and maybe kernel
>>> selection (PowerUP/WarpOS).

>> This is a great idea, i also wish this was possible - but this would
>> mean either:

>> a) Acid Software update Blitz to work on PPCs - but Acid Software no
>> longer exists IIRC.
>> b) Acid Software (or whoever the source is copyright to) release the
>> source to the public for people to port it themselves c) Acid
>> Software licence the porting of Blitz to PPC to another company.

> Actually it would mean:

> d) since a good portion of all Blitz "commands" are in EXTERNAL 680x0
> assembly binaries (called libraries) you would have to re-compile your
> AMiGA specific 680x0 assembly to open, object oriented, superscalar
> PPC code, that can be run using either libraries.

  I think it could be done, but it's not as straight forward as it
looks. You only have (from memory) 11 registers to play with, the other
15 or so free, have to be saved and restored. Also the you have to save
the Gosub return addresses yourself, as there is only a single register
to save it, so as soon as you go down more then one level you have to
save it, and then restore it later, as it's not done automatically like
in the 68k.
 The other big problem, is that you have to do the memory allocation
with the PPC libs not the 68k ones, and also you have to be careful
with the caches, and to not use any memory allocated with the 68k.
  Check out ppctut.lha in dev/asm, this is a very good PPC asm tutorial!
 
  Good luck! :-)

-- 
        Anton Reinauer <anton@ww.co.nz>
      A500,DF1:,0.5MC,8.5MF,60HDD,WB3.1 &1.3/2.0 
    A1200,2M,CD-Rom,25/040,200/PPC ,WB3.0 
          
