@NODE "Mail_85" "Re: Byte to word to long"
From: "David McMinn" <D.Mcminn@eee.rgu.ac.uk>
Organization: The Robert Gordon University, E&EE
Date: Tue, 29 Jun 1999 12:38:18 +0100
Subject: Re: Byte to word to long
Encoding: 8bit
X-UIDL: 871484a860c64db3b78c1a80b946245d

>  Who remembers a couple of weeks back when I complained about a byte
> going negative when it went over 32,000 (at which point, I think it had
> already been 'promoted' to a word)?

You'd do well to get a byte anywhere near 32000.

>  Lots of clever children gave the correct answer- use a long - but I
> suspect this causes slow down (there is already some slowdown, and I
> may just be imagining it). Would using a long make calculations longer?

Probably. As Blitz doesn't optimize for higher processors, it will use the bog-
standard 68000 multiply/add etc instructions, some of which will be 16 bit only 
(probably only multiply/divide, add/subtract should be OK as long versions 
exist). So Blitz will make a longword multiplication into about 4 word 
multiplications, even if some processors have an instruction that can do it in 
1. When you used words, it would also only have taken 1 instruction.

>  The reason I ask is because I'm using the byte to hold the player's
> score. Progress in the game is points based, so upon completing the
> game, the score will be between 28000 and 280064. It only goes above
> 32000 when I go to the 'bonus' screen, and add on bonuses. At this
> point I could change the byte to a long, but I don't know how. Would I
