@NODE "Mail_114" "Re: Depth Scan"
Date:  Sun, 27 Jun 1999 09:24:39 -0300 (ADT)
Sender: John Mason <ah210@chebucto.ns.ca>
From: John Mason <ah210@chebucto.ns.ca>
Subject: Re: Depth Scan
Encoding: 8BIT
X-UIDL: 1644b6c6884d223eaf93ec0be2ca2794

On Sun, 27 Jun 1999, Andreas [ISO-8859-1] Hĺkansson wrote:

> find a file on your hd. You'd specify the root dir to start the scan and it
> would scan threw all folders to look for files mathing your search criteria.
> 
> Now this is not what I'm doing, but the routine is exactlly the same. I know
> all about reading/checking filenames and other info, it's just the scan
> routine that can handel a hiarcy of folders.

Sounds like a job for a recursive function -- you make a function that
reads a dir and say prints the contents, and for any directory it comes
across, calls itself for that directory!  Then it should sift its way
through every directory and as far down as you need to go.  Something like
this should do it (pseudocode):

function .b listdir{dirname}
  lockdir{dirname}
  while (nextdiritem)
    if currdiritem=directory then listdir{currdiritem}
    nprint currdiritem
  wend
end function

I think this should work, I don't know if Blitz allows you to call a
function from within itself, but give it a try.  Someone else may want to
step in if this is totally incorrect. :)


-- 


