@NODE "Mail_150" "Re: ECS/AGA Palettes"
From: Curt Esser <camge@ix.netcom.com>
Date: Fri, 25 Jun 1999 19:08:00 -0500
Subject: Re: ECS/AGA Palettes
X-UIDL: b8e0ebede762bbe5eb0c28d751ddbae2

Hi John

On 25-Jun-99, John Mason wrote:
> 
> I think the AGA chipset was designed so that its palettes would be
> compatible with the OCS/ECS chipset, or at least I seem to remember
> reading that somewhere.

Yes, I thought so too - although it can't be completely compatabile, since
AGA allows 256 "variations" of red, green, and blue for each register.  And
OCS/ECS allow only 16 "variations" of each.

BTW, does anybody know exactly what the difference was between OCS and ECS
(other than the 1M chip on ECS - or was that the only difference?)  

> You could always boot in OCS or ECS and find out
> for sure.

Well, yes, except - I've tried booting in ECS before to test something, and
it worked fine.  But crashed on a "real" ECS systems...  Not this palette
stuff - in fact, I don't remember now exactly what it was  ;)
> 
Later...
-- 

                                    Yours electronically,
                                    Curt Esser
                                    camge@ix.netcom.com
                                    http://members.xoom.com/Curt_Esser/



