@NODE "Mail_151" "Re: ECS/AGA Palettes"
Date:  Fri, 25 Jun 1999 21:34:37 -0300 (ADT)
Sender: John Mason <ah210@chebucto.ns.ca>
From: John Mason <ah210@chebucto.ns.ca>
Subject: Re: ECS/AGA Palettes
X-UIDL: 3d40e4cee8a34c97249e839ee49233ad

Hi Curt,

> Yes, I thought so too - although it can't be completely compatabile, since
> AGA allows 256 "variations" of red, green, and blue for each register.  And
> OCS/ECS allow only 16 "variations" of each.

I think it is, somehow AGA uses two words where ECS used one, and to an
ECS system 255 looks like 15.  I don't remember where I read this though,
maybe in the graphics.library autodocs or something.  Of course it's not
completely compatible with ECS in the sense that there aren't 255 levels
of RG & B though.

> BTW, does anybody know exactly what the difference was between OCS and ECS
> (other than the 1M chip on ECS - or was that the only difference?)  

The ECS Agnus could switch between PAL and NTSC, and the ECS denise
allowed you to use SuperHires and some other special screenmodes, also
larger blits were available, I think -- not sure what other differences
there were.

> Well, yes, except - I've tried booting in ECS before to test something, and
> it worked fine.  But crashed on a "real" ECS systems...  Not this palette
> stuff - in fact, I don't remember now exactly what it was  ;)

A500/020 and see how it works there.


-- 

John Mason   --   ICQ 17931257
