@NODE "Mail_159" "Re: Existing files"
From: Curt Esser <camge@ix.netcom.com>
Date: Thu, 17 Jun 1999 19:12:39 -0500
Subject: Re: Existing files
X-UIDL: 0f525cda2ce26dd6a26d8df02f0bc713

--BOUNDARY.1748684760.1

Hi John

On 17-Jun-99, John Mason wrote:
> Hi Curt,
> 
>> Not much to it, actually.  But I think this will do what you want.  It
>> won't, however, give you the file size of the "found" file.
> 
> Actually, I thought of this, and tried it (locking the file in question).
> It works,  but what if the file has been opened for writing?  It still
> exists, but then the lock would fail (as would Fred's suggestion of
> opening the file, I think).  I suppose I could put up with this, maybe I
> can use a combination of locking and using the Exists command or
> something.  I'll have to do some experimenting.

OK, here's an updated version that will return the DOS error code if the
requested file can't be locked.

                                    Yours electronically,
                                    Curt Esser
                                    camge@ix.netcom.com
                                    http://members.xoom.com/Curt_Esser/


--BOUNDARY.1748684760.1
Content-Disposition: attachment; filename="IsThereERR.asc"

; -- must use amigalibs.res
; -- checks for named file or directory
; -- returns -1 (True) if it can be locked
; -- or the Dos Error Code if it can't

; some error codes you may get:

; 202 - Object in use
; 204 - Directory not found
; 205 - Object not found
; 212 - Object not of required type
; 213 - Disk not validated
; 218 - Device not mounted
; 225 - Not a DOS disk
; 226 - No disk in drive

Function.l IsThere{filename$}
  *lock=Lock_(&filename$,#ACCESS_READ)   ;attempt to lock it
  If *lock                               ;yes, it is there!
    UnLock_(*lock)                       ;release it
    ret.l=-1
  Else                                   ;can't lock it - why?
    ret.l=IoErr_()
  EndIf
  Function Return ret
End Function




--BOUNDARY.1748684760.1

---------------------------------------------------------------------
To unsubscribe, e-mail: blitz-list-unsubscribe@netsoc.ucd.ie
For additional commands, e-mail: blitz-list-help@netsoc.ucd.ie
--BOUNDARY.1748684760.1--




@ENDNODE
@NODE "Mail_160" "Existing Files (the end!)"
Date:  Thu, 17 Jun 1999 21:04:12 -0300 (ADT)
Sender: ah210@chebucto.ns.ca
From: John Mason <ah210@chebucto.ns.ca>
Subject: Existing Files (the end!)
X-UIDL: d7ad649ed22459efe43ebb875e97d538

Hi all,

  I managed to solve my problem with finding out if a file exists _and_ is
0 bytes -- with a combination of Lock() and using IoErr() to get the error
code if the lock fails.  This way I can check for an "Object in use" error
if the lock does fail.

Thanks to everyone who helped.

--

