@NODE "Mail_179" "Forget the Amiga as we knew it (The answer)"
 for scott@online.u-net.com; Sat, 5 Jun 1999 01:12:20 +0000
From: "Jaime Araiza" <jaraiza@mpsnet.com.mx>
Subject: Forget the Amiga as we knew it (The answer)
Date: Fri, 4 Jun 1999 19:10:31 -0600
	charset="iso-8859-1"
Encoding: 7bit
Importance: Normal

Hi!

I've a friend who knows people at Gateway... and I sent the email we
received some days ago... And here is his answer.

--------------------------------------------------------------------

Hey...

Let be the first one to honor all of us here on this list and
be able to shoot this rumor down before anyone can blink.  First off,
this entire message is so out of date it is sick.  It is one persons
view that is currently upset at the situation of not having anything
to show for a computer system that he is wanting to support.  "MRX" is
someone that I can guarantee is not on the "inside" of things, I can
say this without even second guessing.  The reason why is because of
where I work, my other email address is Kent.Seaton@gateway.com.  If
this guy was actually on the "inside" of things, he would have gotten
at least the correct email addresses that work.

Run down of what I do at Gateway:
I am the person in charge of Amiga related questions at
Gateway that come over the internet in the sales department.
Basically if you send in a message to sales@gateway.com, I would be
the one who answers your questions (unless it is to international
waters outside of the United States).  I correspond with all of the
Gateway representatives that have some dealings with Amiga, and this
includes some of the big wigs at Amiga.  Unfortunately I can't say
exactly what I have seen or what is yet to come due to the NDA
agreement that I have signed, but this note made me laugh so hard the
first time I saw it that I had a good chuckle with most of my contacts
in the Amiga community.

It is true that some of what "MRX" says is true (like: most of
the Gateway employees do not even know what the Amiga is) but I can
assure you that I was not hired to sit around and twiddle my thumbs
all day while this awesome technology rots.  Looking back at the email
addresses that were at the bottom of the list you will notice that
there are only three of them that actually still work properly (I
know, cause I have the same email addresses for my contacts) and the
rest are just put there to make you think that the message is true.
Think about this one.  Petro lives in Germany, so why would he have an
AOL account?

Dr. Allan Havemose asked the community not to spread such bad
rumors around but unfortunately, mailing lists and newsgroups thrive
on this sort of thing, not to mention flaming.  Take into
consideration what you have read, and what you have seen.  I can
easily say that if you want good information on what is happening with
the Amiga, then check out the magazines such as Amiga Format or
Amazing Amiga.  Other good places to look for official statements and
postings would be on the Amiga web site itself.  I personally know
that the message has hurt about 40 of my personal friends and has made
them consider leaving the Amiga all together, but keep the faith,
Amiga Inc. will not let you down.  The Amiga is one great community
and I have personally been a part of it since 1987, I am not about to
let it go in a handbasket if I have anything to do with it.
--
Kent Seaton
Gateway Amiga Internet Specialist
mailto:Kent.Seaton@gateway.com
Hours: Friday-Tuesday 8am-5pm, Central Standard Time.
-----------------------------------------------------------------
Amiga: Back for the future!



