@ENDNODE
@NODE "Mail_180" "Re: Forget the Amiga as we knew it (The answer)"
From: Rick Hodger <rick.thehub@bigfoot.com>
Date: Sat, 05 Jun 1999 11:45:06 +0100
Organization: Pagan Software
Subject: Re: Forget the Amiga as we knew it (The answer)
X-UIDL: e04a3f9dcb8d196fe657e70be7170418

I watched as Jaime Araiza hammered "Forget the Amiga as we knew it (The
answer)" out on their keyboard...

> Hi!

> I've a friend who knows people at Gateway... and I sent the email we
> received some days ago... And here is his answer.

> --------------------------------------------------------------------

[SNIP]

> It is true that some of what "MRX" says is true (like: most of
> the Gateway employees do not even know what the Amiga is) but I can
> assure you that I was not hired to sit around and twiddle my thumbs
> all day while this awesome technology rots.  Looking back at the email
> addresses that were at the bottom of the list you will notice that
> there are only three of them that actually still work properly (I
> know, cause I have the same email addresses for my contacts) and the
> rest are just put there to make you think that the message is true.
> Think about this one.  Petro lives in Germany, so why would he have an
> AOL account?

Well, for a start AOL is world-wide.  Oh, and that e-mail address is valid,
it's the account he uses at home.  The reason he uses AOL (I asked him
once) is because he isn't a technical person, and AOL is simple and easy to
set-up and use...even so he barely knows how to use e-mail.  Anyone working
in the computer industry and admitting that has to be brave!

The only reason I know this is becuase he is (or was a few months ago)
subscribed to another mailing list that I get, and he would frequently
answer questions and dispel rumours :)

> Dr. Allan Havemose asked the community not to spread such bad
> rumors around but unfortunately, mailing lists and newsgroups thrive
> on this sort of thing, not to mention flaming.  Take into
> consideration what you have read, and what you have seen.  I can
> easily say that if you want good information on what is happening with
> the Amiga, then check out the magazines such as Amiga Format or
> Amazing Amiga.  Other good places to look for official statements and
> postings would be on the Amiga web site itself.  I personally know
> that the message has hurt about 40 of my personal friends and has made
> them consider leaving the Amiga all together, but keep the faith,
> Amiga Inc. will not let you down.  The Amiga is one great community
> and I have personally been a part of it since 1987, I am not about to
> let it go in a handbasket if I have anything to do with it.

It's no suprise that rumours such as this get started up, I went to the
developer conference at WoA98, where they said about OS4/5 and that the
developer machine would be x86 based, although the new Amiga wouldn't.  It
took about two days for rumours start up that the new Amiga would be a
nasty Pentium machine.

Misheard information really doesn't help, but the fact that the Amiga
community has heard practically nothing from Amiga Int/Inc in the past few
months, it's no wonder people start speculating (which of course turns into
rumours).  The only things we've heard from Amiga in the past while, are
some promo gimicks, a concept drawing or two, and that they've hired a load
of people.  Oh, and of course dates for releases of new machines/OS's that
probably won't come to fruit (Remember, last year they said that the new
Amiga would have been ready by now and the dev machine would have been
available for about 6-9 months).

The Amiga community, in my opinion, doesn't want to hear about the latest
"Amiga Mobile Phone Covers" or "Amiga Matches", they want to hear something
more along the lines of "OS3.5 is nearly finished" or "OS5 is progressing
well, during the last month we added an updated CD File System" or
whatever.  We want to hear more than the latest promotional gizmos - we
have Amiga's, we like Amiga's, you don't need to sell them to us!

Oh, and the likes of Amiga Format rarely have information that wasn't
available elsewhere on the internet about a month or two previously to the
magazine's publishing date.

>Kent Seaton
>Gateway Amiga Internet Specialist
>mailto:Kent.Seaton@gateway.com
>Hours: Friday-Tuesday 8am-5pm, Central Standard Time.

-- 
<sb>Rick Hodger - Programmer for #Pagan Software#
<sb>
