@NODE "Mail_181" "Forget the Amiga as we knew it (The answer)"
From: bml@thenet.co.uk (Simon Archer)
X-FTN-To: All
Subject: Forget the Amiga as we knew it (The answer)
Date: 05 Jun 1999 17:12:40
X-newsreader: Spot 1.3b #1534
Encoding: 8bit
X-UIDL: 815cdb57605cab3e9da6ffd32d04ce09



On 5 Jun 99 Rick Hodger wrote about 'Forget the Amiga as we knew it (The answer)'.

 RH> Oh, and the likes of Amiga Format rarely have information that wasn't
 RH> available elsewhere on the internet about a month or two previously to
 RH> the magazine's publishing date.

Unfortunately, that's one of the problems with the publishing industry. Most
computing magazines will be the same, as the news tends to always break on a
more realtime medium like the internet.

Bear in mind also, that due to NDA's etc, there is only so much news that can
be told. Public news is free for print, but public news gets here first.

Amiga have made moves towards supporting the Amiga press, and have said that
some news will be held back and given to magazines first so that these snippets
can be broken by the mags instead. You may have noticed the Amiga Press site at
amiga.com, and this is exactly what it is intended for.

Simon Archer



