For additional commands, e-mail: blitz-list-help@netsoc.ucd.ie



@ENDNODE
@NODE "Mail_196" "Re: Framerates of MonitorDrivers"
From: "Dave" <dave@nbsamiga.demon.co.uk>
Subject: Re: Framerates of MonitorDrivers
Date: Sat, 19 Jun 1999 01:00:39 +0100
	charset="iso-8859-1"
Encoding: 7bit
X-UIDL: 2e2522fb747558162bc9a7990ca7d430

Hi Curt,

>Sometimes it is handy to have some code executed by a VBlank interrupt.
>Then you don't need to worry about constantly checking the time in various
>parts of your code to see if it is time to execute it.  Also, the interrupt
>code will still continue executing even if the rest of the program is
>"sleeping" while waiting for an event.


Yep I get that, I have that in my kart game. But the kart game is
multiplayer (over the internet), and all times are sync`d to one second, and
I use the time to tell me the gap since the last update (in micros+secs) and
then I work out where the cars should be and what speed. (I couldn`t see a
way of syncing it to frame rates, as gfx cards could be different and pal
and ntsc are different, meaning that over a long period of time, the ntsc
player would have gained some extra movement as it`d never be exact).

>You also need to wait for the VBlank when doing double-buffering, to
prevent
>flickering.  So it's useful to know how often it will occur.


Yep..but you just need that to sync to, you don`t need to know how many per
second they are. I know there are uses for it, but even when I`ve been
working on the video player, it doesn`t need to know how the framerate, just
the fps of the video (ie, you only need to display x per second with the
vblank as a sync). And that makes it more flexible with different framerates
and time used per game cycle.

Guess I`m just mulling over stuff...I always used to use framerates for
everything..but I never do now...weird or what!! (guess it`s the os friendly
programming style taking hold)

Dave




