@ENDNODE
@NODE "Mail_197" "Re: Framerates of MonitorDrivers"
From: Anton Reinauer <anton@ww.co.nz>
Date: Mon, 21 Jun 1999 14:10:48 +1200
Subject: Re: Framerates of MonitorDrivers
X-UIDL: a197a71ea38c1481534faf1ca5d4d312

On 19-Jun-99, Dave wrote:
> Hi Curt,

>> Sometimes it is handy to have some code executed by a VBlank
>> interrupt. Then you don't need to worry about constantly checking the
>> time in various parts of your code to see if it is time to execute
>> it. Also, the interrupt code will still continue executing even if
>> the rest of the program is "sleeping" while waiting for an event.


> Yep I get that, I have that in my kart game. But the kart game is
> multiplayer (over the internet), and all times are sync`d to one
> second, and I use the time to tell me the gap since the last update
> (in micros+secs) and then I work out where the cars should be and what
> speed. (I couldn`t see a way of syncing it to frame rates, as gfx
> cards could be different and pal and ntsc are different, meaning that
> over a long period of time, the ntsc player would have gained some
> extra movement as it`d never be exact).

  Yeah, but yours is a 3D type game, with a 2D game you'd want to check
your framerate is correct. AFAIK you can only use certain preset
framerates, or you'll end up skipping the odd character animation
frame, which won't look nice. With a low framerate like 25fps, I would
say any frame skips would be noticible- maybe with higher rates you
could get away with it (but you'd need higher res screens to get higher
animation rates in your animations too). Having a variable framerate in
3D games is definately the way to go, but I can't see any easy way of
doing it in 2D :-/ 
 
 Also, I checked the docs on CurrentTime which you suggested using for a
timer:

    This time value is not extremely accurate, nor is it of a very fine 
    resolution.  This time will be updated no more than sixty times a
    a second, and will typically be updated far fewer times a second.

  I was thinking that for a multi-player game timer, this would add in
more variance into the timer system, so effectively adding to the
effects of lag :-/ I'm going to have a play with the EClock Timer, as
the docs say it's very accurate over long time periods, and also you
can easily check the rate it's running at as well (I assume only NTSC
or PAL). The only problem is other programs can change it's value :-/ 
   So I'd have to do a check each time it's accessed to make sure it's
in the correct bounds from the last access- also, I was thinking you
could run a CIA interrupt as well, as a safety check! And maybe re-sync
it with the EClock every know and again to compensate for load variance
in the CIA timer. Then if someone reset the E-Clock you could use the
CIA variable to adjust the number you now would be getting from the
E-Clock :-)  Also I'll have the Server do regular checks that the
Clients clocks are still in sync with it's own. 

  Seeya- Anton

-- 
        Anton Reinauer <anton@ww.co.nz>
      A500,DF1:,0.5MC,8.5MF,60HDD,WB3.1 &1.3/2.0 
    A1200,2M,CD-Rom,25/040,200/PPC ,WB3.0 
          
