--BOUNDARY.1748400280.2

Hi Gareth

I've attached a version of your source converted to a look-up-table rather
than all those "If/Then"'s

Although I've used a NewType for the LUT, you could use a standard
multi-dimension array if you prefer.

Dim LUT.b(36,1)

Then store the x-offsets in LUT(i,0) and the y-offsets in LUT(i,1)  

I find the NewType easier to follow, myself.

On 06-Jun-99, Gareth Griffiths wrote:

> The attached files are:
> 
> GTAtest.asc     -   ASC source code of the prog
> GTAtest.bb2     -   Tokenised code.
> GTAtest.xtra    -   ??? What do these xtra files do?

The .xtra file is a record of everything you have set in your compiler
options - number of objects, compiled exec name, debugger on/off, any
resident files being used, etc.
So you don't have to re-set them when you load your sources.

Usually, there is no need to distribute it - unless you have set some of the
objects to something greater than the defaults.

For distributing source code, always use an ascii version.  There is no
point in ever sending the tokenized source, as it won't work on some
people's systems and the ascii version is automatically converted to
tokenized source if you load it into Blitz and save it out again.

If you need to send the .xtra file, just rename it to match the ascii
filename (in this case, it would be "GTAtest.asc.xtra" and include it with
that name.  Blitz will then load it with the ascii source - the file
extensions (other than .xtra) mean nothing to Blitz.



                                    Yours electronically,
                                    Curt Esser
                                    camge@ix.netcom.com
                                    http://members.xoom.com/Curt_Esser/


--BOUNDARY.1748400280.2
Content-Disposition: attachment; filename="GTA.LUT.asc"

WBStartup : NoCli : CloseEd
Screen 1,0,0,640,512,5,$8004,"",1,2
BitMap 1,640,512,5
LoadPalette 1,"GTAcar.anbr" : Use Palette 1
LoadShape 1,"GTAcar.anbr",1
Cls 0
Buffer 1,16384
img=10
plx=100 : ply=100

;--------- set up a look up table and fill in the offsets

NEWTYPE.offsets   ;for the look-up-table
  xoff.b
  yoff.b
End NEWTYPE

Dim LUT.offsets (36)

;the x offsets
Data.b -5,-5,-4,-4,-3,-3,-2,-2,-1,0,1,2,2,3,3,4,4,5,5,5,4,4
Data.b 3,3,2,2,1,0,-1,-2,-2,-3,-3,-4,-4,-5

;the y offsets
Data.b 0,-1,-2,-2,-3,-3,-4,-5,-5,-5,-5,-4,-4,-3,-3,-2,-2,-1,0
Data.b 1,2,2,3,3,4,4,5,5,5,5,4,4,3,3,2,2

For i=1 To 36
  Read temp.b
  LUT(i)\xoff=temp
Next
For i = 1 To 36
  Read temp
  LUT(i)\yoff=temp
Next

;-----------------------------------------------------------

ShowBitMap 1
BitMapOutput 1
VWait
Colour 31,0
Repeat
  pass+1 : If pass>50 Then pass=1
  If pass=50
    Locate 0,0 : Print "X: "+Str$(plx)+"     Y: "+Str$(ply)
    UnBuffer 1
    BBlit 1,img,plx,ply
    VWait
    If Joyx(1)=-1 AND Joyy(1)=-1
      img-1
      If img<1 Then img=36
    EndIf
    If Joyx(1)=1 AND Joyy(1)=-1
      img+1
      If img>36 Then img=1
    EndIf
    If Joyy(1)=-1

      plx+LUT(img)\xoff   ;this replaces all the If/Then stuff
      ply+LUT(img)\yoff

      If plx<=20 Then plx=20
      If plx=>620 Then plx=620
      If ply<=20 Then ply=20
      If ply=>450 Then ply=450
    EndIf
  EndIf
Until Joyb(1)=1



--BOUNDARY.1748400280.2

