@NODE "Mail_218" "Re: Grand Theft AMiGA (Oh no, not again!)"
From: "Linda Bell" <zalda@home4968.freeserve.co.uk>
Subject: Re: Grand Theft AMiGA (Oh no, not again!)
Date: Tue, 8 Jun 1999 18:26:22 +0100
X-UIDL: 711c532400acc1d11729a2b62d2205e7

Gaz,

Another thing you might consider with a scrolling game, is that it
might be better to use a one-dimensional array of strings, instead
of a two-dimensional array of bytes/words - as it is often quicker
to peek strings, than access arrays - especially if the game is
vertically scrolling - as you would only need to get the address
of the string once for each row.  You would MAXLEN the string to
the width of the map.  Also, using strings means that you can peek
bytes, words or longs, thereby holding two tiles in one variable,
which you can then access by using "AND $FF" or "LSR 8", instead of
accessing an array twice.  Try some speed tests.

Also - if you save the maps as data files, it means you can NPRINT/
EDIT$ lines of text, instead of bytes in an array.  Though you need
to watch out for Chr$(10), if memory serves me right, as this is a
linefeed - took me ages to figure out why my maps weren't displaying
properly :)  I always use this method, as then I can edit a font to
reflect the tiles of the map, and write a quick intuition-based
map-editor - with the tiles on button gadgets, and I can simply
NPRINT the map to the screen, and peek/poke new values in when I
click the mouse on the map.  Yes I know there are tons of map-editors
on Aminet, I just prefer this method.

VIC

Don`t know if this first attemp at ansi will display properly...
