@NODE "Mail_219" "Re: Grand Theft AMiGA (Oh no, not again!)"
From: "Linda Bell" <zalda@home4968.freeserve.co.uk>
Subject: Re: Grand Theft AMiGA (Oh no, not again!)
Date: Tue, 8 Jun 1999 18:47:58 +0100
X-UIDL: 440e5b27e73fb85e8c7aac28a6ce951d

Anton

>> I assume Anton means if you use blockscroll - well, you can scroll
>> very quickly without using blockscroll, ignore the examples given in
>> the Blitz manual and examples drawers - they`re too slow. I`ve got a
>> very fast scrolling routine that I used with George2 - it`s not fast -
>> it`s supersonic.
>
>  On an OS screen/window? If you can I'd be /very/ interested! My game
>does hardware map-scrolling in Blitz mode, but superbitmaps in a window
>in AGA scroll horridly! :-) I've got it working in Qamiga, but I don't
>know how stable it is long term :-/


Ah... I use blitz-mode, but I would think you could use scroll or bitmap to
window or something - I was thinking of doing something on this scroll
routine for the BUM that gaz is doing.  But like Fred said, basically, if
you`re using 16x16 tiles - then for every pixel you scroll the screen, you
block one tile vertically, off the screen and by the time you`ve gone 16
pixels, you`ve completed one column that is about to appear, and can start
on the next.  The problem is when you get to the end of the bitmap - the
Blitz manual recommends using BlockScroll to copy the end of the bitmap back
to the start, but the simple answer is to look-ahead to see at what point
the bitmap will be flipped back, and then, as with the above, block one tile
behind you for each pixel you scroll the screen - though this means having
two bitmaps that are larger than 2 screens wide for double-buffering.

This way, you don`t get one frame where the CPU has more work to do, as it
does with BlockScroll, as it is always blocking the same number of tiles
each frame.

VIC




