On 09-Jun-99, V Bell wrote:
 
>>> I assume Anton means if you use blockscroll - well, you can scroll
>>> very quickly without using blockscroll, ignore the examples given in
>>> the Blitz manual and examples drawers - they`re too slow. I`ve got a
>>> very fast scrolling routine that I used with George2 - it`s not fast
>>> - it`s supersonic.

>>  On an OS screen/window? If you can I'd be /very/ interested! My
>> game does hardware map-scrolling in Blitz mode, but superbitmaps in a
>> window in AGA scroll horridly! :-) I've got it working in Qamiga, but
>> I don't know how stable it is long term :-/

> Ah... I use blitz-mode, but I would think you could use scroll or
> bitmap to window or something - I was thinking of doing something on
> this scroll routine for the BUM that gaz is doing.

  I tried everything I could think of, and Bitmap to Window is sloow and
jerky, as it seems to copy the whole bitmap :-/  If you use Show in a
Window, and double-buffered bitmaps it runs at 50fps fine, but when you
try to scroll, it runs slow! You would think that if you can switch
bitmaps, you should be able to display a certain section of the bitmap
just as easily and have it run at 50fps :-s
    Maybe you could play around with bitmap pointers to achieve the
effect, but I'm not that up on OS stuff, and it doesn't seem worth the
effort for new games which will use Chunky and C2P anyway :-)

> But like Fred said,
> basically, if you`re using 16x16 tiles - then for every pixel you
> scroll the screen, you block one tile vertically, off the screen and
> by the time you`ve gone 16 pixels, you`ve completed one column that is
> about to appear, and can start on the next. The problem is when you
> get to the end of the bitmap - the Blitz manual recommends using
> BlockScroll to copy the end of the bitmap back to the start, but the
> simple answer is to look-ahead to see at what point the bitmap will be
> flipped back, and then, as with the above, block one tile behind you
> for each pixel you scroll the screen - though this means having two
> bitmaps that are larger than 2 screens wide for double-buffering.

> This way, you don`t get one frame where the CPU has more work to do,
> as it does with BlockScroll, as it is always blocking the same number
> of tiles each frame.
 
   Yes, my game Pyromid uses this method in Blitz mode for it's 50fps
horizontal Map-Scrolling. 
  You can use it with Chunky bitmaps as well, but if you're going to
have lots of objects onscreen which have to end up being Unbuffered to
restore the background, you might as well just draw the entire
background, and objects on top each frame. It'd probably end up taking
the same amount of time anyway, especially if you start doing things
like lighting effects on the background (can I hear echoes from Paul
here! :)

-- 
