--BOUNDARY.1748480208.2

Hi Anton

On 09-Jun-99, Anton Reinauer wrote:
> On 08-Jun-99, Curt Esser wrote:
> 
>>> On an OS screen/window? If you can I'd be /very/ interested! My game
>>> does hardware map-scrolling in Blitz mode, but superbitmaps in a
>>> window in AGA scroll horridly! :-) I've got it working in Qamiga, but
>>> I don't know how stable it is long term :-/
> 
>> I once did some experiments with scrolling in Amiga-mode, by using an
>> oversized screen and bitmaps, and doing the scrolling by moving the
>> entire screen. It worked nice and smoothly on my 030/50 with up to 128
>> colours.
> 
>   Could you send me the code?  I could then convert Pyro-Mid as it
> stands then, because it's set up to run at 50fps :-)

Well, here is as far as I got with the idea - I gave it up when I found it
wouldn't work on GFX cards.  But it could be useful for a modem-based game
where you need to multi-task.

It really doesn't do anything yet - no graphics or double buffering - really
just a test to see if the idea would work at all.
> 
>> You can also duplicate Blitz-mode "slices" by using child screens so
>> you can have, for example, a scrolling game area on top with a
>> stationary "control-panel" on the bottom.
> 
>  Yes, cool idea!

The test code shows a small "Score" area at the top (it's actually a
separate
screen).  This wouldn't work for vertical scrolling, since the bottom
screen would cover it if you scrolled up.  But a separate screen at the
bottom would work for both vertical and horizontal scrolling.

BTW, the idea for this came from the paint program Brilliance.

Also, the separate screens don't have to be the same depth (or even the same
resolution, for that matter)

I don't know if you are using the mouse in your game.  If you are, it is
possible to eliminate the auto-scrolling and confine the mouse to the
visible area of the screen.

If you have any questions, let me know.

>  Yes, I was thinking I could do it for AGA, and then maybe a Window
> with a chunky buffer for GFX cards- it would only be for the old game
> though- for a new game, I'd just use Chunky :-)

Yeah, that's the way to go these days.

                                    Yours electronically,
                                    Curt Esser
                                    camge@ix.netcom.com
                                    http://members.xoom.com/Curt_Esser/


--BOUNDARY.1748480208.2
Content-Disposition: attachment; filename="OS.Scroll.asc"



;NEEDS amigalibs.res, WB 2.xx or better

WBStartup

Format "000"

Statement showscore{score}    ;this really shows screen position
  Use Screen 0                ;for the example
  Use Window 0
  WLocate 20,4
  NPrint "Score :",Str$(score)
  Use Screen 1
End Statement

;------- first, the score display screen

sDisplay.l=69632        ;NTSC lo-res
sDpth.w=3               ;screen depth
sWidh.l=320             ;screen width
sHeit.l=25              ;screen height

Dim SCRtags.TagItem(10)

SCRtags(0)\ti_Tag=#SA_DisplayID,sDisplay
SCRtags(1)\ti_Tag=#SA_Quiet,True           ;no titlebar
SCRtags(2)\ti_Tag=#SA_ShowTitle,False
SCRtags(3)\ti_Tag=#SA_Depth,sDpth
SCRtags(4)\ti_Tag=#SA_Width,sWidh
SCRtags(5)\ti_Tag=#SA_Height,sHeit
SCRtags(6)\ti_Tag=#SA_Top,0
SCRtags(7)\ti_Tag=#SA_Left,0
SCRtags(8)\ti_Tag=#SA_Pens,?DriPens        ;List of 13 Dripens
SCRtags(9)\ti_Tag=#TAG_DONE

ScreenTags 0,"",& SCRtags(0)    ;open the test screen

Window 0,0,0,sWidh,sHeit,$1000|$800,"",1,0 ;an invisible window
Menus Off

*par=Peek.l(Addr Screen(0))   ;for attaching the two screens together

;-------- now, the "Game" screen ------------------------------

Display.l=69632        ;NTSC lo-res
Oscan.w=1              ;overscan setting - need this!
Dpth.w=4               ;screen depth
Widh.l=640             ;screen width
Heit.l=200             ;screen height

Dim GAMtags.TagItem(13)

GAMtags(0)\ti_Tag=#SA_DisplayID,Display
GAMtags(1)\ti_Tag=#SA_Overscan,Oscan       ;needed or mouse will "wrap around"
GAMtags(2)\ti_Tag=#SA_Depth,Dpth
GAMtags(3)\ti_Tag=#SA_Width,Widh
GAMtags(4)\ti_Tag=#SA_Height,Heit
GAMtags(5)\ti_Tag=#SA_Top,20
GAMtags(6)\ti_Tag=#SA_Left,0
GAMtags(7)\ti_Tag=#SA_AutoScroll,1         ;autoscroll is on!
GAMtags(8)\ti_Tag=#SA_Pens,?DriPens        ;List of 13 Dripens
GAMtags(9)\ti_Tag=#SA_Quiet,True           ;no title bar
GAMtags(10)\ti_Tag=#SA_ShowTitle,False
GAMtags(11)\ti_Tag=#SA_Parent,*par         ;this screen is attached to screen 0
GAMtags(12)\ti_Tag=#TAG_DONE

ScreenTags 1,"",& GAMtags(0)    ;open the test screen


Window 1,0,0,300,100,$1000,"Screen info",1,0  ;and a small window
Menus Off

Format "########"
NPrint "Display ",Display
NPrint "Depth=",Dpth
NPrint "Oscan=",Oscan
NPrint "Use joystick to scroll"
NPrint "Press joystick button to end"

Window 2,310,0,300,100,$1000,"I'm here!",1,0 ; a second window
Menus Off

NPrint "Hiya!"

screenx.w=0
showscore{screenx}


moveamount.b=2                             ;number of pixels to move


Repeat                                     ;loop until button pressed
  Select Joyx(1)                           ;detect joystick left/right movement
    Case -1                                ;joystick to left
      MoveScreen 1,moveamount,0            ;move screen to right 1 pixel
      If screenx=>moveamount Then screenx-moveamount
      showscore{screenx}
    Case 1                                 ;joystick right
      MoveScreen 1,-moveamount,0           ;move screen left 1 pixel

      If screenx<=(320-moveamount) Then screenx+moveamount
      showscore{screenx}
  End Select
  If Joyb(1) Then End                      ;end when a button is pressed
Forever

Even
DriPens
Dc.w  0,1,1,2,1,3,1,0,2,1,2,1,-1





--BOUNDARY.1748480208.2

