--0-1189641421-929844325=:25946
Content-Description: Carfix.txt
Content-Disposition: inline; filename="Carfix.txt"

<blitz-list@netsoc.ucd.ie>
<Grand Theft AMiGA (Oh no, not again!)>

Hello Gareth Griffiths. Wiremu here.

> This is my first bit of non-WB programming in blitz. It does NOT use
> Blitz mode, 'cos some peeps said that if i did that, it would be
> unfriendly to gfxboards etc.

I don't have a graphics board myself. My question to all those gfx
board people out there is; What ever happened to using Blitz mode
since it stops everything else in its tracks therefore devoting its
run time to the game?

> I have the car reacting to joystick movements, going forward, rotating
> etc. But, when the car reaches about half way down the screen, it
> starts to flicker horribly.

Okay. I've given your program a double-buffering screen. I'm making
the assumption you don't know what this is based on your 'flickering
horribly' remark.

A double buffer is made up of two screens. The whole idea behind this
system is that the computer draws up the new position of the blits on
one screen while displaying the other. When its finished drawing, it
swaps the screens. The previous screen becomes the new drawing
display while the finished drawing become the screen you see. It
sounds longwinded, but it makes sense in the code.

The disadvantage of double buffers is that it being two screens it
takes up twice as much memory. If memory isn't a problem on your
Amiga then no worries, but it may be a problem on other peoples
Amigas (640x512x5x2? Aarrgghh!).

  *******************************************************************
  My OTHER question is does an Amiga with a graphics card need double
  buffering? I've seen some Mildred demos that don't have any for the
  c2p setup, and they don't have any. Can you program your program to
         DETECT graphics cards (Use Mildred perhaps you idjiot)?
  *******************************************************************

> The code is attached. The joystick rotation part is fairly simple, but
> the code executed when you push up on the joystick is quite
> longwinded, cos I didn't know any other way. Any ideas on this
> gentlemen (and ladies, if there are any out there!)

I've made a Newtype array for your joystick code. It's still fairly
longwinded, but I think it will optimise your code. I understand that
a large series of IF statements can make compiled code bigger.

On the subject of car driving stuff, try this address:

http://esewww.essex.ac.uk/~cdimita/blitz/Model1.html
        "                   "           /Model2.html

It's from the BLITZ PAGE with documentation on discrete time modeling.
It's all pretty basic stuff, but it is comprehensive, and it'll help
you think of ways of structuring your car stuff together properly.

------------------------------------------------------------------------------

WBStartup : NoCli : CloseEd

NEWTYPE .xy ; Although these things can be awkward to use,
x.w         ; Newtypes ultimately make things easier for you
y.w         ; (and the computer) to organise.
End NEWTYPE

Dim Image.xy(36) ; This is a 2d array because of the Newtype!

USEPATH Image(a) ; So you won't have to type out Image(a)\x
For a.b=0 To 36  ; Image(a)\y instead just \x,\y.
Read \x,\y       ; I gave 'a' a .b value because it only stores
Next a           ; whole numbers (not fractions) between 0-255!

Screen 1,0,0,640,512,5,$8004,"",1,2

; Allow me to introduce you to double buffering.

BitMap 0,640,512,5
BitMap 1,640,512,5

; I changed the name of your file (it's a long story) I suggest
; you change it back.

LoadPalette 1,"GTAcar.ab" : Use Palette 1
LoadShape 1,"GTAcar.ab",1

Cls 0
Buffer 0,16384    ; Double buffering means two buffers ;-)
Buffer 1,16384

img.b=10       ; Same rule applies here as for 'a' otherwise it
db.b=0         ; defaults to .q (quick) which uses fractions.
pass.b=1       ; it gives it less to think about.

plc.xy\x=100,100  ; Because it's 2d, you can insert 2 values
                  ; simultaneously

ShowBitMap 1
BitMapOutput 1
VWait
Colour 31,0

USEPATH Image(img)
Repeat
  pass=QWrap(pass+1,1,51)
  If pass=50
    Use BitMap db
    BitMapOutput db
    Locate 0,0 : Print "X: "+Str$(plc\x)+"     Y: "+Str$(plc\y)+"  "
    UnBuffer db
    BBlit db,img,plc\x,plc\y
    ShowBitMap db
    db=1-db                  ; Swap screens!
    VWait

; Like you said you wanted this bit shorter.
; ------------------------------------------
    j.b=Joyr(1)
   plc\x=QLimit(plc\x+\x,20,580)     ; Set up movement
   plc\y=QLimit(plc\y+\y,20,450)
    Select j
      Case 7
        img=QWrap(img-1,1,36)        ; Turn left
      Case 1
        img=QWrap(img+1,1,36)        ; Turn right
      Case 0
        ; do nothing!                ; Straight ahead
      Default
       plc\x=QLimit(plc\x-\x,20,580) ; Else
       plc\y=QLimit(plc\y-\y,20,450) ; Undo set up movement
    End Select
; ------------------------------------------
;                   HOWZAT?!!
  EndIf
Until Joyb(1)=1
End

.init

; Here's what happened to all those IF statements.

Data.w -0,-0
Data.w -5,-0,-5,-1,-4,-2,-4,-2,-3,-3,-3,-3,-2,-4,-2,-5,-1,-5
Data.w -0,-5, 1,-5, 2,-4, 2,-4, 3,-3, 3,-3, 4,-2, 4,-2, 5,-1
Data.w  5,-0, 5, 1, 4, 2, 4, 2, 3, 3, 3, 3, 2, 4, 2, 4, 1, 5
Data.w -0, 5,-1, 5,-2, 5,-2, 4,-3, 4,-3, 3,-4, 3,-4, 2,-5, 2

------------------------------------------------------------------------------

