@NODE "Mail_228" "Re: Grand Theft Double Buffering"
From: "Linda Bell" <zalda@home4968.freeserve.co.uk>
Subject: Re: Grand Theft Double Buffering
Date: Mon, 7 Jun 1999 18:35:52 +0100
X-UIDL: 722bd7ede0085fa676f9fff320bb590f

Rui wrote,
>Don't use If ... Then ..., that burns cycle time.
>
>E.G. -» If eggs=boiled then eat_them else let_them_boil
>
>The compiler has to run run through the entire if line to see if there are
any
>exceptions or more code.
>
>instead use
>
>If eggs=boiled
> eat_them
> more_things_to_do_here
>else
> let_them_boil
>Endif
>
>This way the compiler jumps to the next instruction/exception if the
condition
>is not what you needed...
>--
>Best Regards,


Hmm.   I`ve often wondered about this - I remember programming in Borland
Turbo Pascal 5 - and there was an option to switch on Short-circuit boolean
logic, so that the above wouldn`t happen - I wasn`t sure whether Blitz did
or not - always intended to write a test program to time it - but have been
using the method you mention in the meantime anyway.  Why it doesn`t
short-circuit is beyond me - it would seem the obvious thing to do.

VIC




