@NODE "Mail_266" "Re: Hex Numbers Again"
From: "David McMinn" <D.Mcminn@eee.rgu.ac.uk>
Organization: The Robert Gordon University, E&EE
Date: Fri, 2 Jul 1999 17:30:35 +0100
Subject: Re: Hex Numbers Again
Encoding: 8bit
X-UIDL: 9f21e86d4c75060591cac5b196e672aa



> But how do I get Blitz to recognise this as a Hex number?

You can't, its a string :)

> This number needs to be passed to a OS command for controlling AHI
> volumes, so in the command you manually enter $10000 (full volume)

What, like SetAHIVolume($10000)?

> Now that works, but if I use
> 
> Val(Hex$(64*1024) 
> 
> or 
> 
> Val(Hex$(65536) 
> 
> which are the same, Blitz will obviously
> think it's just a Decimal number (probably because of the VAL, but Hex$ by
> iteself doesn't work either) i.e. 10000 being placed into the command but
> I need it to regonise it as a Hexadecimal number......

Numbers are numbers, it doesn't matter how they look in a program, they are all 
stored in (relatively) the same way. Decimal is hex, just written differently 
so that lame biological species like ourselves can count on our fingers :) And 
vice versa.

> Any ideas?? The AHI docs state that the number passed must be a
> 
>     LONG Fixed; 16bits to the left of the point and 16bits to the right.
> 
>     Maximum Volume is 1.0 (0x10000L) or $10000 in Blitz terms
>     Minimum volume is 0.0 (0x0L) or $0 in Blitz terms
> 
> Can someone please help with this?

Get yourself a quick variable, that is what a long fixed is equivalent to. Then 
pass it as SetAHIVolume(Peek.l(&myqeek)) so that Blitz doesn't convert the 
quick to a long (i.e. cutting off the lower word because that represents 
fractional values in a quick, which a long obviously can't do). Make sure it 
doesn't go above 1 or below 0 though.

Or use a long, and never let the value go above 65536 or below 0.


