@NODE "Mail_283" "Re: Including a picture - with NCS-Libs"
Date: Fri, 25 Jun 1999 18:31:10 +0200
From: Frederic Laboureur <alphasnd@sdv.fr>
Subject: Re: Including a picture - with NCS-Libs
Encoding: 8bit
X-UIDL: 63d866f0ead9aa733fe8b56f63066c40


	Hello,

	Sorry, but you CAN'T read the palette from an included picture
with actual NCS command.. But why would you include pictures in
your main executable ? I don't like this technique so much, because
it eats constantly memory for NOTHING ! Imagine, you include an 60 kb
picture in your code. Ok. You will have an 70 kb executable. When you
want to display the picture, you will allocate a bitmap (60 kb) and copy
the picture in it. BUT it's always resident in memory, so 120 kb is used
instead of 60 kb. When you read the file content in the buffer, you open
it, read it, and finally close it and free all the memory ressource...

		Think about that.. A stuff you can do is to add the file after the compiling
and use some special tricks to read back the data from your 'executable+data'

			Good bye,

                        Fred.

