Hi John

On 22-Jun-99, John Mason wrote:
> On Tue, 22 Jun 1999, David McMinn wrote:
> 
>> > This might be your problem. If this was C, it would be correct, but
>> > since in Blitz "true" is -1, instead of any positive value like in C,
>> > you won't get the results you're after. However, this should just
>> > always fail, not crash!
>> 
>> Nope, Blitz works the same as C in this respect.
> 
> Wow, you're right!  :)  I can't believe I never caught onto that! ;)
> "True" is -1, but >0 is also true, which makes the reason his code was
> crashing a total mystery I guess...

To be perfectly accurate, False=0, and anything else, positive or negative,
is considered "True", at least in Blitz.

Using "-1" to mean "True" is simply a convention, like using "i" and "j" for
loop variables.
> 
Later...
-- 
I haven't lost my mind; it's backed up on tape somewhere.

