@NODE "Mail_324" "Re: I`m gonna take up C again"
From: Curt Esser <camge@ix.netcom.com>
Date: Wed, 23 Jun 1999 16:41:51 -0500
Subject: Re: I`m gonna take up C again
X-UIDL: cec935327395565e8d0f3eb5e4dc39fc

Hi Vic

On 23-Jun-99:

> No, I don`t think it`s the beepscreen giving the problem, as I tried
> NPrint as well. At the moment, my program opens the library if it`s there,
> and disables/enables the V37 gadgets as appropriate - it`s just that it
> crashes if the translator.library isn`t there at all. Still, anyone
> downloading it really ought to have the library anyway.

Ahh, there was more to the program, then?  Yes, I think Blitz will attempt
to open any needed libraries or devices needed right away, when the program
first starts, before executing any code.  So if your program uses the
translator.library and the narrator.device, Blitz will try to open them
first, before doing the check I think...

Although, the problem is possibly that the narrator.device is also missing?

Anyway, a couple of possible solutions:

1} An installer script, that checks the versions (and existance of) the
translator.library and narrator.device (and anything else your program
needs) - if either is missing, or too old, the script could then abort with
a "sorry, this program requires blah blah blah..." message.

2} A little "loader" program, which would be just the code for checking for
the required library and device.  If successful, it would then run the main
program and exit, if not it could put up a requester with the "sorry"
message.
> 
> VIC
> 
> BTW - this might be the last you hear from me - I`m trying to install
> extra memory in this PC, but windows won`t boot - the premium rate help
> desk told me I need to reinstall windows after putting the memory in
> Grrrrrr. I don`t remember having this problem with Workbench!

Sounds like fun!  I only ever had to install WorkBench once, when I upgraded
to 3.1 years ago.  I'm still running on the same installation (and HD, for
that matter) even though that was 2 systems and countless hardware upgrades
ago...

So much for "Plug & Play", eh?

-- 

