> it.  And the the yank press dosn't call it would cup but something
> else.

> Then there me at U-Net which is .Com which is in the UK.  

All ".com" means is commercial. ".org" means a non-profit making site, and
".net" means a networked system.  But because they are much more generic
(unlike ".org.uk" etc) they tend to be a bit cheaper than country specific
ones.  Funny how everything comes down to money eh?

> The world is mad!  And security I am leader of all.  Billy Gates
> is a nobody next to me.

My work runs a country specific free ISP, for Northern Ireland
(www.nireland.net) and yet the vast majority of visitors come from (a)
american uni's (b) local rivals and (c) people who've signed up for every
other freebie service under the sun (screaming.net, freeserve, hotmail,
yahoo, freenet, Club 24, Talk 21 and far too many others to list).

Oh, and three quarters of the people who do sign up for dial-up accounts
appear to be from Devon.  Are devons tight fisted gits? Who knows! :)

But frankly, it doesn't really seem to bother people whether a site has a
country specific address or not.  If it's free they'll take it :)

