@NODE "Mail_349" "Re: Look-up tables"
From: Daniel Allsopp <daniel@thesnakepit.demon.co.uk>
Date: Tue, 08 Jun 1999 00:34:16 +0100
Subject: Re: Look-up tables
X-UIDL: 031203a03fccb0b32f691e4d311b2da0

Hi Gareth,

On 07-Jun-99, you wrote:

> Hi,
>  Yeah, but how do I do 'em in Blitz? And how would I make them realte
> to Grand theft amiga (AKA Crimewave)

Well I use them in my game (Operation: Counterstrike) as a part of the
artificial intelligence to decide which way the little tank should rotate
from it's current direction.

Really, all a LUT is, is a normal blitz array with pre-calculated values in
it.

First,

*Dim LUT(8,8) *

this is 8 goto-directions, and 8 current-directions, i.e. the direction the
tank is in (1=North, 2=North-East, 3=East, so on) and the direction you
want it to go to, same numbers.

You must give the object somewhere to go, and obviously its current
direction is already there.

So in my LUT I've got directions as :

TRUE=Rotate ClockWise
FALSE=Rotate Anti-Clockwise

Here's a small example.

*LUT(1,3)=True* ; This means, that if the direction he's in is 1 (North) and
he wants to move to direction 3 (East) the value in the LUT is true.

Then in the main code something like this,

Just assume he's facing North and you've just clicked East,

*current_direction=1*
*moveto_direction=3*
**
*If LUT(current_direction,moveto_direction)=True*
*    Turn Clockwise*
*Else*
*    Turn Anti_Clockwise*
*End if*

I use this system for my units which have 32 frames each, 8 main directions
and 3 in-between frames for each of those directions. Using this method
makes it a lot clearer to understand. Or maybe not......this was probably a
bad example but it saves plenty time in the game.

If you need more explanation give the list a shout again, I'm sure someone
will help and give a better example.

-- 
Cheers,
    Daniel

<tsb>E-Mail: daniel@thesnakepit.demon.co.uk
<tsb>URL: http://www.thesnakepit.demon.co.uk/
