@NODE "Mail_362" "misplaced windows"
 for scott@online.u-net.com; Wed, 2 Jun 1999 13:24:39 +0100
From: Curt Esser <camge@ix.netcom.com>
Date: Wed, 02 Jun 1999 07:11:37 -0500
Subject: misplaced windows

Hi everybody,

Here's a very odd one.  It has to do with my Crazy8 game, if you've seen it.

Anyway, the program uses it's own screen, and 2 bitmaps for double-buffering
(one of these is the Screen's bitmap) as well as an assortment of windows:

A full screen permanent "invisible" window for tracking the mouse and
reading keypresses, as well as an assortment of windows that open and close
when needed for the menu, scores, etc.  I also use ASL filerequesters and
ReqTools button requesters.

OK, all this mess works fine as long as you stay on the game screen.

But sometimes (and it only happens rarely here, which is what makes it such
a pisser) if you go to the WB or other screen and do something else while
the game is running, the window positions get messed up.  Meaning that
instead of opening at, say 20,20  the window will open at around 200,80. 
And it's not predictable - it's not always the same wrong position every
time this happens on different runs.

And when it does happen, all windows (including requesters) will open at
this same wrong position.  Not only that, but they also "wrap-around"
right-to-left and bottom-to-top.  It's as if Intuition has somehow lost
track of my screen's top left corner or something.  Also, sometimes some of
the bitplanes of the window (or requester) seem to be missing - (wrong
colours or a "negative" effect) but this doesn't always happen.

The window and requester opening positions are all "hard-coded" (ie,
specified directly in the commands - no variables are used) except for the
reqtools requesters, which are set to center themselves.

This all happens only if the game screen is left, but it doesn't seem to
matter if it is left by using the game's "hide" button, by using a hotkey,
or by dragging the screen down.

It also is completely unpredictable - usually, there is no problem.  But
sometimes if I run certain other programs it will happen - sometimes
running the very same other program doesn't cause a problem.

I'm hoping maybe someone else has run into this before, and (fingers firmly
crossed) found a cure?  Or at least knows what is doing this?

Thanks for any ideas...  

Later...
-- 
The Law of Least Astonishment:
The most obvious way of doing something is the correct way.

                                    Yours electronically,
                                    Curt Esser
                                    camge@ix.netcom.com
                                    http://members.xoom.com/Curt_Esser/



