Subject: Re: misplaced windows

Hi David

On 02-Jun-99, David McMinn wrote:
> 
> 
>> Hi everybody,
> 
> Hi Dr. Nick
> 
>> Here's a very odd one.  It has to do with my Crazy8 game, if you've seen
>> it.
> 
> <snip>
> 
>> Thanks for any ideas...  

> What other programs do you need to run for it to happen? That might give
> some idea for a starting point even though you said it was random.

It seems more prone to happen with programs that use MUI - or sometimes it
will happen if I've used the Blitz compiler to compile & run it, then make
an exec, then quit Blitz and run the exec.

But again, I could try doing any of this 20 times, and it will all run fine.
 It only pops up when I'm convinced I've gotten it fixed for good   ;)

And it never happens on a fresh boot - only when the system's been on a
while, and I've run and quit so many things I've lost track...

Oh, also I had at one time tried using the function that you and James Boyd
wrote that moves the mouse pointer and clicks the buttons.  With that in
the program, I could get this to happen consistantly if I hid the game's
screen and ran any MUI program.  I don't think it's anything with the
function itself, as it still does this very rarely even without it, but
maybe a clue? 

> Also
> what libs/commands are you using in C8s?

Everything but the kitchen.synch.library  ;)

All the window & screen commands, reqtools commands, the bitmap, shape,
sound, and blitting commands, as well as the GT commands and standard
ShapeGadgets, the Elmore.dos stuff, the palette commands (both Blitz and
RI), the pointer commands, and a bunch of OS functions too. 
> 
> Are you closing the windows and re-opening them?

Yes, except the main window which is always open.  But it's invisible, so I
can't tell if it's been moved.

Oh, I forgot to mention that when this happens, Intuition responds to the
gadgets in the various windows being pressed where they should normally be,
rather than where they are shown.  In other words, if I press where the
"quit" button normally would be, the "quit" button gets shown as pressed
where it is now drawn (not under the pointer), and the game exits as
usual...

> Or are they just going
> ape and moving?

No, if one window is opened in the correct place, as long as you stay on the
game screen they all will work properly.  And stay still (none are
draggable or re-sizable)

The windows are all accessed through the "menu" window's buttons, so of
course it must be open first.  And if it's OK, the rest are all ok.  If
it's displaced, all the rest will also be displaced exactly the same
distance.  And even the displacement distance is not consistant.

On one occasion it might be hardly noticable and the next time it could be
half the screen off, with the window split into 4 parts something like
this:

Normal:

---------------------------------
|                               |
|                               |
|                               |
|   -----------------------     |
|   | I'm a window ;)     |     |
|   -----------------------     |
|   |                     |     |
|   |                     |     |
|   |---------------------|     |
|   |        QUIT!        |     |
|   -----------------------     |
|                               |
--------------------------------- 

Displaced:

---------------------------------
|            |        |         |
|------------|        |---------|
|IT!         |        |       QU|
|-------------        ----------|
|                               |
|                               |
|                               |
|                               |
|                               |
|--------------       ----------|
|ndow ;)      |       | I'm a wi|
|--------------       ----------|
---------------------------------


But once it happens, it's permanent for the rest of the time the game is
being run.
And also, if this happens, sometimes the game will quit OK - sometimes
quitting causes a "program failed" requester, sometimes a total guru.  And
if it does quit OK after this happens, running it again sometimes will
cause a guru or a "recoverable alert" followed by a guru...
 

                                    Yours electronically,
                                    Curt Esser
                                    camge@ix.netcom.com
                                    http://members.xoom.com/Curt_Esser/



