@NODE "Mail_398" "Re: narrator.device"
From: Curt Esser <camge@ix.netcom.com>
Date: Sat, 12 Jun 1999 22:50:09 -0500
Subject: Re: narrator.device
X-UIDL: cfbbaad5b961eca770543c8bf043ddf1

--BOUNDARY.1749306736.2

Hi Vic

On 12-Jun-99, Linda Bell wrote:
> Hello ppl,
> 
> I`ve got a problem [fortunately, the doctor gave me some cream :)].
> 
> In the meantime, I`m updating my first ever program, which uses the
> speak-handler, and the narrator device. When I quit the program, these two
> objects are still in memory. Does anyone know if there is a way to find
> out if any other program is using them, and if not, shut them down?
> 
> While I`m at it, the same goes for fonts.

Here is a function by James Boyd that may help.  The problem is, the stuff
won't be flushed if some program is still using it. 

Well, you can free the font(s) with:

Free Intuifont 0  (or whatever)

But I don't know how you can "free" the narrator.device before your program
ends.  Of course, Blitz should free it automatically when your program ends
- but then, you can't do the FlushMem function anymore...

You might have to open and close it yourself (see the autodocs) rather than
using the Blitz commands.

The speak-handler is "Mounted" by the OS, like a disk drive.  I don't think
it can be "un mounted"...  Maybe it does if the narrator.device is closed
down?

                                    Yours electronically,
                                    Curt Esser
                                    camge@ix.netcom.com
                                    http://members.xoom.com/Curt_Esser/


--BOUNDARY.1749306736.2
Content-Disposition: attachment; filename="FlushMem"
Encoding: quoted-printable

;-----------------------------------------------------------------

; Statement : FlushMem {}

; Author : James L Boyd - jamesboyd@all-hail.freeserve.co.uk

; Same as calling "Avail Flush" from the CLI.

; This makes sure your program has as much free memory as
; possible before starting, loading files, etc.

; Note that some programs don't like having memory flushed at
; certain times (this is the same with "Avail Flush" though),
; so use sparingly!

; Note that there's no need for this to check the return value
; - it's ALWAYS zero!

; This is the way described in the docs for PoolMem, and
; if you run a program called MemPatch (from Aminet), you'll
; see that "Avail Flush"  does exactly the same thing ("Avail
; Flush" calls this about 10-15 times though, each time, so
; maybe you'll want to do that...)

; Also, this clears out unused libraries, fonts, etc as well,
; because they get freed only when memory's low, and I think
; this call makes them believe that's the case...does work
; though :)

Statement FlushMem {}
  AllocMem_ $7ffffff0,#MEMF_PUBLIC
End Statement

; demo :

;; NOTE - if there's not much memory to be freed, you
;; sometimes find that you lose a few bytes while your
;; program's trying to free the memory, but try running
;; and quitting something big, like Voyager, or calling it
;; right after you've done a whole load of programming
;; (after you've saved your work, obviously!!!), and you
;; should see a big difference...

; NPrint ""
; av1.l=3DAvailMem_ (#MEMF_PUBLIC)
; NPrint "Available memory : ",av1," bytes."
; NPrint ""

; FlushMem {}

; av2.l=3DAvailMem_ (#MEMF_PUBLIC)
; NPrint "Available memory : ",av2," bytes."
; NPrint ""
; NPrint "Freed ",-(av1-av2)," bytes." ; if printed number's negative, it=
's used memory!
; NPrint ""
; NPrint "Click mouse..."
; MouseWait:End

;-----------------------------------------------------------------


--BOUNDARY.1749306736.2

