@NODE "Mail_400" "Re: narrator.device"
From: James L Boyd <jamesboyd@all-hail.freeserve.co.uk>
Date: Sun, 13 Jun 1999 14:28:39 +0100
Subject: Re: narrator.device
X-UIDL: ceb65eccd184e8ab2e0fb193e19ae747

--BOUNDARY.1749052048.1

Curt Esser churned out *this* drivel:

>> In the meantime, I`m updating my first ever program, which uses the
>> speak-handler, and the narrator device. When I quit the program, these
>> two objects are still in memory. Does anyone know if there is a way to
>> find out if any other program is using them, and if not, shut them down?
 
> Here is a function by James Boyd that may help.  The problem is, the stuff
> won't be flushed if some program is still using it. 

Yeah, that tries to allocate an impossible amount of memory (and fails), but
it makes the OS clear out all the crap to try and accommodate it...

The attached code will just flush the narrator device...it's a tiny
modification of the FlushLib {} statement in StatsFuncs.lha...

See ya,
-- 
<tsb>
<sb>James L Boyd - jamesboyd@all-hail.freeserve.co.uk
<sb>Member of Team *AMIGA*, and *Dogbert's New Ruling Class.*
<sb>Connected from Dundee, Scotland. 
<sb>(http://surf.to/all-hail/)
<tsb>

Don't let it end like this. Tell them I said something.
-- last words of Pancho Villa

--BOUNDARY.1749052048.1
Content-Disposition: attachment; filename="RemDevice.asc"
Content-Description: Removes specified device if it's not in use...

; use XOpa or similar to make sure narrator.device isn't
; in use (reboot or remove if it is), then run the say command
; (eg. say hello). You should now be able to update the device
; list in XOpa and see the narrator device, which doesn't get
; freed (not here anyway). Run this and update again and it
; should be gone :)

; only works if nothing else is using it, and you don't get any return
; value from RemDevice_() so you'd just have to check for it again if
; you want to make sure (thugh there's not much you can do if it hasn't
; been removed)...

Statement FlushDevice {device$}

*exec.ExecBase=Peek.l(4)
*mylist.List=*exec\DeviceList

    Forbid_
      *devnode.Node=FindName_ (*mylist,&device$)
      If *devnode
          RemDevice_ *devnode ; can't tell you if it succeeded :(
      EndIf
    Permit_

End Statement

; demo :

FlushDevice {"narrator.device"}
End



--BOUNDARY.1749052048.1

