@NODE "Mail_415" "Re: narrator.device - furthermore"
From: Curt Esser <camge@ix.netcom.com>
Date: Mon, 14 Jun 1999 13:17:45 -0500
Subject: Re: narrator.device - furthermore
X-UIDL: 50be9fe79fcaf846cc6096eb71b26ac4

Hi Anton,

> Check out:  http://www.amigaprog.freeserve.co.uk/files/
> 
>  There's some updated docs on the narrator.device with all the
> SetVoice stuff and translator lib.

I downloaded this archive.  But now I have a problem with speech stuff.

First, I should say I did have the old 1.3 speech files -
translator.library, narrator.device, and speak-handler.

The archive I downloaded had a newer translator.library and narrator.device,
but no speak-handler.

So, I replaced the translator.library and narrator.device with the newer
versions from the archive.  And it all seemed to work fine.  I tested Vic's
Mr.Wolf program, as well as the old 1.3 SpeechToy and MUIspeak.

Well, the speech stuff worked fine with all of them, and sounds better than
the old 1.3 version.  But, with all 3 programs, I would get "Recoverable
Alert" messages, or sometimes "Program Failed" requesters on exiting. 
Also, programs that require a lot of chip mem wouldn't work properly while
any of these programs were in use, although the title bar still showed over
1.4k of available chip ram.  But, for example, Ppaint would open only a
tiny screen instead of my usual default full hi-res-laced overscan 256
colour screen, and would report not enough chip ram to open a requester.

It seemed like the speech stuff was somehow blocking access to a huge chunk
of chip ram, and not freeing it on exiting...

This all definately was due to the newer library or device, replacing them
with the old ones solved all the above problems.

So, the question is, does anybody know what's wrong?  Do I also need a newer
"speak-handler" with the newer library or device?  Or is something else
missing?

Or were the files on that website corrupted somehow?  Did anybody else have
a similar problem.

Could anybody possibly send me a copy of the 2.xx versions that works on
their system?

l/speak-handler
devs/narrator.device
libs/translator.library


Thanks for any help.

                                    Yours electronically,
                                    Curt Esser
                                    camge@ix.netcom.com
                                    http://members.xoom.com/Curt_Esser/



