From: Curt Esser <camge@ix.netcom.com>
Date: Mon, 14 Jun 1999 22:04:16 -0500
Subject: Re: narrator.device - furthermore
X-UIDL: 5ad4bd539c5e530811fb88dbcbd19903

Hi Ashley

On 14-Jun-99, Ashley Scott wrote:
> On 14-Jun-99, Curt Esser Wrote........
> Hiya Curt,
> Give this a try.... It works for me without any problems on a A1200 040-40
> 34mb.  I've set everything to the correct dir's so it's a peice of piss to
> set up.  I've also made a dosDriver for the Speak handler.  TTFN

Thanks - and thanks also to James Boyd and Vic Bell, who also sent copies.

But, the problem still remains  :(

I've narrowed it down to the v37.7 narrator device itself.  And also
discovered that the problem is NOT with chip ram.  Rather oddley, it seems
to be compleyely fragmenting my FAST ram!

Before running any "talking" program (including the C examples that are in
the archive itself) my AVAIL command reports over 12.5M fast ram available,
with the largest block being almost that much.

But once a "talking" program is run, it still shows about 12M free, but now
the largest block is about 40k -  Yes, that's right, 40k !!!!!  Oh, and
just executing the AVAIL command now causes a "recoverable alert"

Exiting the program leaves me with a largest available block of fast ram at
about 70-80k...

And, as before, putting back the old narrator.device (I have v33.2) cures
it...

Does anyone have a version newer than 33.2 but not 37.7?

Hmmm, maybe this is why they dropped it in OS 3.xx???

                                    Yours electronically,
                                    Curt Esser
