@ENDNODE
@NODE "Mail_436" "Re: narrator.device - v37 features"
From: Curt Esser <camge@ix.netcom.com>
Date: Fri, 18 Jun 1999 18:13:08 -0500
Subject: Re: narrator.device - v37 features
X-UIDL: d8e2fe7b8a44f3c9cb178d2cc3bfd2eb

Hi Vic

On 18-Jun-99, Linda Bell wrote:
> After messing about with the v37 stuff, I just thought I`d mention that
> the newvoice structure in Blitz sets all the new variables up as BYTEs -

You will often run into unsigned bytes or words in OS structures.  (It is
actually accessing the internal variables in the narrator.device, so don't
alter the NewType or it won't work - you might even meet the GURU...)

> not a problem, unless you`re using slider gadgets to set the values, as
> some go from 0-255, and since Blitz doesn`t provide a UBYTE, you have to
> be careful with WORDS and BYTES.

You can use bytes (and words too) as unsigned in Blitz if you need to (like
in this
case).
Just make sure you have Overflow Errors turned off in your compiler options.

There really isn't a difference between a signed/unsigned byte - it's just
in reading it. In signed, one of the bits is read as a +/- sign rather
than a numerical value as I understand it - in any case, a byte is always a
group of 8 bits, no matter what you store in it. 

You can store any value from 0 ~ 255 in the byte just by a.b=210 or
whatever.

And you can read a byte as unsigned with something like NPrint a AND $FF -
this will always give you the unsigned value of the byte.

Oh, and for unsigned words, the same trick applies - just use AND $FFFF to
read a word as unsigned.

Try this bit of code (overflow errors off, please!):

a.b=213
nprint a          ;wrong results, negative value
nprint a AND $FF  ;hey!  it worked!
mousewait
end

                                    Yours electronically,
                                    Curt Esser
