@NODE "Mail_458" "Re: None"
Sender: parnaudeau@wanadoo.fr
Date: Mon, 28 Jun 1999 09:15:44 +0200
From: Mathias PARNAUDEAU <mathias.p@wanadoo.fr>
Organization: wanadoo.fr
Subject: Re: None
Encoding: 8bit
X-UIDL: 3245a012d11bac5a603a737a7dee9f47

Le 14-Juin-99, Leigh Parry a écrit:

>Hello,

Hi Leigh,

>I have a problem (well more than one, but we won't go into them ;-)

>how can i prevent the following code from causing an enforcer hit , this code
>is similar to some in a prog i'm working on and I believe the only Enforcer
>hits are caused by this code. ( AGARed ,etc.)

Yes, your program causes hits with my system too.

>How else colud i stor the pointer colours withouth having to go into too much
>depth ( I might drown ;-)

I think I have a soluce but you have to catch the Wb palette.

After that, just get the palette object address :
   addr.l = peek.l(addr palette(0))

Add 4 to addr.l (the 4 bytes contain the palette size or the number of
colors,
I don't remember ) :
   addr.l + 4

For each color you have 4 bytes per component (I don't know why) :
   color 0 : rrrxgggxbbbx
   color 1 : rrrxgggxbbbx
   ...

x is a unknown (reserved ?) byte.

To get the red, green and blue values of color c :
   redvalue = peek.b(addr.l+c*12) AND $ff
   greenvalue = peek.b(addr.l+c*12+4) AND $ff
   bluevalue = peek.b(addr.l+c*12+8) AND $ff

I suppose it works ...

Good luck,

-- 
          Mathias PARNAUDEAU - Corto/AFLE

Email    : mathias.p@wanadoo.fr
Site Web : http://perso.wanadoo.fr/supersport/

