@NODE "Mail_494" "Overscan and other quirks"
From: Donovan Reeve <bubby.lnk@ispi.net>
Date: Sat, 19 Jun 1999 08:23:36 +0500
Subject: Overscan and other quirks
X-UIDL: 2c4cf292ec13d93b11bb300cbf6f51f4


Hi all,

  I have been exploring the limits of what can be accomplished in Blitz
as far as screen size, shape and color depth combinations as for
several of my games I wish to use unusual screen/display/bitmap
combos.  I have discovered some rather interesting things, some rather
cool possibilities and some rather irksome limitations.

  By the way, thanks to Simon Hitchen, Curt Esser, and Paul West
(unfortunately no longer with us) for your helpful information.

  One of the major questions I have is how well some of these things
will work for the overall Amiga userbase, and how far it is safe to press
the limits without making my software unuseable on a significant portion
of Amiga user's machines.  One of the major issues is of course the
limited chip ram, and how much of it the average user has used for other
purposes.  This is one of the major reasons I have decided that I may
continue to use Blitz mode and not try to make my games multitask.  I
know this has been a major issue for a long time, but I just can't see
limiting my games just so something else can exist in the background.
Also, the point of multitasking a game would be so that a person could
have a job processing in the background while they play, but realistically,
how many people actually do this to any significant degree?  Also,  any
game which uses any significant amount of processor and other system
resources is going to slow the background work to a crawl, and is
going to crawl itself and be no fun due to the background work going on.
It would be better to play the game, have fun, and then let the work
proceed at full speed while you sleep.
  Hitting the hardware may be unpopular, and may cause future compatibility
problems, but that is why game consoles are so popular, because they use
their system resources fully for the game and do not waste any of it on
the dubious idea of running more than one thing at once.  Multitasking is
WONDERFUL for applications where working in several programs at once is
an advantage, but for games, it stinks IMHO.  Background music is a
totally 'nother issue however.  I don't use it, but my kids can't live
without it.

  Comment invited on the above.


  So...  I have been seeing how far the system will stretch...
but I don't want to break it.  In other words, I want my stuff to run on
everyones Amigas as much as is reasonably possible.  My goal is to have
certain games run on ECS and 2mb each of chip and fast ram, and other
games run on all AGA machines with at least 4MB of fast ram, and 2 of
my games will be aimed at higher-end Amigas with 68040/25 absolute
minimum for processor and 8mb of fast ram needed with up to 32mb being
used to speed things if available and sound and graphics boards supported.

  But to begin with, I need to find out what is possible on the various
Amiga configurations out there, so to finally get to the point, I'll
be needing people to try a few very short test programs for me and
hopefully make suggestions as to how to optimise system useage more.

  Any willing guinie pigs?



Donovan Reeve (bubby.lnk@ispi.net)



---------------------------------------------------------------------
