Hi Donovan

On 18-Jun-99, Donovan Reeve wrote:
> 
> Hi all,
> 
>  I have been exploring the limits of what can be accomplished in Blitz
> as far as screen size, shape and color depth combinations as for
> several of my games I wish to use unusual screen/display/bitmap
> combos.  I have discovered some rather interesting things, some rather
> cool possibilities and some rather irksome limitations.

>  One of the major questions I have is how well some of these things will
> work for the overall Amiga userbase, and how far it is safe to press the
> limits without making my software unuseable on a significant portion of
> Amiga user's machines. One of the major issues is of course the limited
> chip ram, and how much of it the average user has used for other purposes.
> This is one of the major reasons I have decided that I may continue to use
> Blitz mode and not try to make my games multitask. I know this has been a
> major issue for a long time, but I just can't see limiting my games just
> so something else can exist in the background. Also, the point of
> multitasking a game would be so that a person could have a job processing
> in the background while they play, but realistically, how many people
> actually do this to any significant degree? Also, any game which uses any
> significant amount of processor and other system resources is going to
> slow the background work to a crawl, and is going to crawl itself and be
> no fun due to the background work going on. It would be better to play the
> game, have fun, and then let the work proceed at full speed while you
> sleep.
>  Hitting the hardware may be unpopular, and may cause future
> compatibility problems, but that is why game consoles are so popular,
> because they use their system resources fully for the game and do not
> waste any of it on the dubious idea of running more than one thing at
> once. Multitasking is WONDERFUL for applications where working in several
> programs at once is an advantage, but for games, it stinks IMHO.
> Background music is a totally 'nother issue however. I don't use it, but
> my kids can't live without it.
> 
>  Comment invited on the above.

Well, really the main reason people are moving away from Blitz-mode
programming is that it won't work on GFX cards, which a lot of people use
these days.  If you aren't concerned about supporting GFX cards, there is
really no reason to avoid Blitz mode if you find it suits your purposes
better.

I also am not sure if Blitz-mode programs will run on systems using monitors
that require DoublePal or DoubleNTSC modes?

Or if sound cards will work?

I have neither myself - I use a PC multi-synch monitor with a flicker-fixer,
and properly written Blitz-mode programs do work for me, as well as
Amiga-mode games and programs, so I personally don't care which method you
use ;)

However, as far as processor-time, it is quite simple to give your game a
high priority so it will get all the processor power it needs, if that's
your main concern.

And as a program user, I (and most other people, I would think), do have
enough sense to kill other tasks if I find them slowing down a game I want
to play...

And I should point out that I often run across hardware-hitting games that
refuse to work on my system (written in Blitz and other languages) - but I
think it's mostly due to bad programming.

> 
>  But to begin with, I need to find out what is possible on the various
> Amiga configurations out there, so to finally get to the point, I'll
> be needing people to try a few very short test programs for me and
> hopefully make suggestions as to how to optimise system useage more.
> 
>  Any willing guinie pigs?

Sure, I'm happy to try whatever you send along.

I have 68030/50 AGA  2Mchip 16fast


