Donovan Reeve wrote:

>
> Also, the point of multitasking a game would be so that a person could
> have a job processing in the background while they play, but realistically,
> how many people actually do this to any significant degree?

I frequently have a large job printing in the background, and I'd love to have
a decent game to play while I'm waiting for it to print.

> Also,  any
> game which uses any significant amount of processor and other system
> resources is going to slow the background work to a crawl, and is
> going to crawl itself and be no fun due to the background work going on.

Often when I'm printing, I find that one of the speed limitations is not the
processor but the parallel port.  CPU utilisation sits at just above 50% when
transfer takes place and only spikes to 100% during processing of the page.
I'd rather play a game for an hour while my page prints than sit around doing
nothing for half an hour.

> It would be better to play the game, have fun, and then let the work
> proceed at full speed while you sleep.

That depends on how noisy the work is.  A printer can be qute loud.

> Multitasking is
> WONDERFUL for applications where working in several programs at once is
> an advantage,

It also allows your programs to be improved by others, e.g. Civilisation has a
horrible save game system, but because it uses the system a commodity is
available to redirect save game files to whereever you like.

>  Comment invited on the above.

You've got it.

>   Any willing guinie pigs?

I have an A1200, 68030/50 with FPU and 32 mb fast ram

