@NODE "Mail_512" "Re: Point and Plot."
From: Curt Esser <camge@ix.netcom.com>
Date: Sun, 20 Jun 1999 07:17:00 -0500
Subject: Re: Point and Plot.
X-UIDL: 7fce4c52bfefbacd3021e5fe6bf9bd08

Hi Linda

On 20-Jun-99, Linda Bell wrote:
> Rob wrote,
>>   Is there a faster way to point/plot? Has anyone got a faster ASM
>> way to do this? Or another lib that does this job better?
>> 
>> Failing that, does anyone know how these commands work?
>> I think it`s just determining the offset inside the bitmaps data
>> from the X/Y coords and then peeking the RGB values????
>> Anyone know the structure of the raw bitmap data?
>> 
>> The point and plot command in blitz are the slowest 2 gfx commands
>> I`ve seen to date!! Esspecially for what they do!!. Just 1 sodding
>> pixel man :(
>> 
>> Any ideas anyone?
> 
> 
> Well you could try the NCommandSet 1.9 which Fred has just put on Aminet -
> I think NPlot is faster, but I agree that it would be much simpler to find
> the bitmap in memory, and peek the value there, OR it with what we want to
> plot, and then poke it back.

Err, it's not quite that simple guys - the above method would work for an
8bit Chunky, where each pixel is represented by one byte which is the
colour register number of that pixel - but a BitMap is actually set up as a
series of bitplanes, depending on the depth of your screen.

A 256 colour bitmap for example would consist of 8 separate bitplanes -
think of it as 8 sheets of paper stacked on top of each other.  Each pixel
is represented by a series of bits stacked on top of each other in the same
position on each "sheet".
To read the colour of one pixel you would need to peek at 8 different bytes,
extract the single bit in question from each, then combine these into a
byte to get the colour register number.  That is why it takes so long.

I did some experiments in colour-remapping and found that it is actually
faster to convert a planar bitmap to a chunky, then do the plotting on
that, then convert it back to a planar bitmap for display.

                                    Yours electronically,
                                    Curt Esser
                                    camge@ix.netcom.com
                                    http://members.xoom.com/Curt_Esser/



