@NODE "Mail_517" "Re: Point and Plot."
From: Curt Esser <camge@ix.netcom.com>
Date: Mon, 21 Jun 1999 06:20:55 -0500
Subject: Re: Point and Plot.
X-UIDL: 09cf6ad7adc037778abb1926bbd91062

Hi Rob

On 20-Jun-99, Rob Hutchinson wrote:

> Didn`t think it was, and after testing somewhat, it`s pretty hard.
> See the attached.. I still dont know what I`m doing, dont spoze ya can
> point me in the right direction?
> But you can see that I dont know what I`m doing cant you.. ahahahaha.
> 
> Anyway, it`s only a test. I was just seeing if I could poke different
> colour registers to the bitmap, but I haven`t got a clue how to do that
> :((((... I change the _data[x] to 0,1,2 or 3 and it changes colour, but
> anything over and it throws a wobbley and spacks your mig :(

Well, maybe this will help a bit - actually I don't know how to do binary
conversions and such either, but I can tell you what needs to be done, and
maybe someone else knows the maths to do it?

First, let's say we have an 8 bitplane bitmap (256 colours) and we want to
change the second pixel from the top left.  To make it simple, let's say
that the first 8 pixels are now all colour 3, except the second one, which
is colour 25.

In binary, 3=00000011 and 25=00011001

So, the first 8 bits of each bitplane would be:

bitplane1 00000000
bitplane2 00000000
bitplane3 00000000
bitplane4 01000000
bitplane5 01000000
bitplane6 00000000
bitplane7 10111111
bitplane8 11111111

To change the second pixel to colour 58 we need to change these so the
second column (reading vertically) would be 00111010.

To do this, you would need to get a pointer to your bitmap, as you have
done.  Then, you must read in the correct byte from each of the 8
bitplanes, change the correct bit, (in this example the second from the
left), and then store the new bytes back into the same places.

As you can see, it's a lot of work.  And to do it any quicker than Fred's
NCS routine (or even the Blitz command) would be quite a job.  It would
have to be done in ASM, of course.

Depending on how much "plot"ing you are doing, it might be faster to just
blit some 1x1 shapes instead?



                                    Yours electronically,
                                    Curt Esser
                                    camge@ix.netcom.com
                                    http://members.xoom.com/Curt_Esser/



