@NODE "Mail_524" "Re: Point and Plot."
From: Toby Zuijdveld <hotcakes@abacus.net.au>
Date: Sat, 26 Jun 1999 13:29:45 +1000
X-SenderInfo: 1;
   picture="http://www.geocities.com/SunsetStrip/Disco/6065/a1people/tobyzuij.gif"
Organization: =?iso-8859-1?Q?Res=A1stance?=
Subject: Re: Point and Plot.
Encoding: 8bit
X-UIDL: 376a5c14fa3f1ff070b748ba6b6c9f02

Hello Thomas

On 21-Jun-99, Thomas Cobb set out across the seas with this message:

TC>> That is why it takes so long.
TC>> What was the point in this then? To reduce memory that the Bitmap takes

TC> No, the bitmap is still taking up the same amount of space. I think the

Well, only if it uses 8 bitplanes.  If it uses less than 8 bitplanes then it
uses less space, obviously =] And since the Amiga came out when 16 colour
graphics cards on the IBuM were THE thing and since the Amy could only manage 6
bitplanes at first I don't suppose it made sense to use a chunky format.  (ie
always 8 bits)

TC> reason is that in this form the data is easier to manipulate if you want to
TC> do scrolling. Compare scrolling 2D games on the Amiga to those on the PC and
TC> you'll notice the difference.

Also makes it a helluvalot easier to do those funky psychadelic effects used in
all the olllllld demos =]

Regards
-- 

