@NODE "Mail_525" "Pointy things, or the plot thickens!"
From: Donovan Reeve <bubby.lnk@ispi.net>
Date: Thu, 24 Jun 1999 20:49:51 +0500
Subject: Pointy things, or the plot thickens!
Encoding: 8bit
X-UIDL: 1c0e81ec9c9dc1da361b380ce4bfee40

On 21-Jun-99, Mikkel Lřkke flashed:


>I suggest moving to a chunky library, like Mildred, or the NCS. It's a bit
>slower at rendering stuff, and requires min 030. But you can have everything
>in FAST ram, and do all kinds f specil effects, really really fast. See the
>Mildred homepage for some examples.


  The Boxer, which I have had on order for over a year, will be capable of
being upgraded to a NG Amiga (a recent developement) and also has removed
the 2mb chip-ram limitation (another recent developement).  These things
combined with the addition of PCI slots and a change to high speed DIMMs
instead of SIMMs all have changed the character of the machine a bunch!
It will truely be an ideal bridge machine to the NG, with a G3 card and
the parallel processor slot being of open architecture and able to support
whatever new processor the NJ Amigas may have on the 64 bit processor buss.
Of course, if the NG Amigas come out right away as 128 bit machines it
still won't be as good, but as I said, it will be an ideal bridge machine.
The production config Boxer motherboard is due to finish final testing in
about two weeks and first shipments (with all these new goodies) are
aimed at the end of July.  The new additions will definately be worth
the additional two and a half months wait (from the May 15 target date).
Oh, by the way, Anti-Gravity also plan to include AmigaOS 3.5 if it is
available by then.

  I am going to have a lot of fun with Blitz on this new unfettered
Amiga.  I plan to get a NJ Amiga also when the become available but it
will likely be a year or two before something like Blitz is available
for it, and even though I have C++ I don't find myself liking to use
it like I do Blitz.  With Blitz2, Mildred and NCS and my new Boxer, I
will be set to enjoy life untill the NG Amiga gets rolling.  I probably
will never get rid of my old Amigas, I'll just keep them around for
old times sake. But the Boxer I expect to be genuinely useful for
many years yet with the changes Access have made recently.


cach y'all later,

Donovan Reeve (bubby.lnk@ispi.net)



