@NODE "Mail_530" "Re: Power Basic Examples ;))"
From: "David McMinn" <D.Mcminn@eee.rgu.ac.uk>
Organization: The Robert Gordon University, E&EE
Date: Wed, 30 Jun 1999 13:16:39 +0100
Subject: Re: Power Basic Examples ;))
Encoding: 8bit
X-UIDL: bee2636aed2baa2a17676e469a0254fc

Hi Fred,

Very good work!

> >I'd like to ask a couple of question if I may, as it might affect my
> >decision to continue with writing my game Blitz instead of switching to
> >C++.

I hope you're not speaking about Counterstrike, Daniel. Could give a whole load 
of hassle if you've done a lot of code, i.e. rewriting it.

> >1) Can PB compile code for specific 68K processors? i.e. special faster
> >versions for 040 or 060.
> 
>  Not with the first version... BUT the PowerBasic could, yes. BTW, it use
>  the
> phxass 680x0 assembler, so it support any assembler instruction and can do
> little optimization for 020+ processor. And you could write 040 special
> PowerBasic sub library is you want (c2p, fast move...)

Ahh, right so you convert code to ASM then use whatever assembler is available? 
How easy will this be to extend it to different processors? Now that Amiga have 
said that AmigaSoft will be for lots of processors.

> >2) How easy is it to import BB2 code into the compiler. Is there a
> >converter or will it require major rewrites for PB?
> 
>  It's very easy to switch from one to other. Count about half day for a
>  large code...

Depending how quickly you work of course ;)

> >3) Will there be an option to use Blitz Libraries? i.e. Mildred for PB or
> >would Mildred have to be re-written specifically for PB?
> 
>  Definitely NO. Because the structure of them isn't the same at all. PB
>  one is much more complex.

But of course the PB one is better. Will it be possible to make your own 
libraries, like with Blitz?


