	Hello Dave

>>  Not with the first version... BUT the PowerBasic could, yes. BTW, it use
>>  the
>> phxass 680x0 assembler, so it support any assembler instruction and can do
>> little optimization for 020+ processor. And you could write 040 special
>> PowerBasic sub library is you want (c2p, fast move...)
>
>Ahh, right so you convert code to ASM then use whatever assembler is
available? 

	Yes ! You guess it :). I've asked the permission to Frank (coder of phxass
and pasm)
to use these assembler to compile the PB output.

>How easy will this be to extend it to different processors? Now that Amiga
have 
>said that AmigaSoft will be for lots of processors.

	Not very very difficult. To pass from 68000 to PPC is relatively easy because
you have more register on the PPC than on the 68000 (twice more! 32 instead
16).
BUT I've looked how do an x86 version and hum, I've only 4 registers under
windows, whish is not enough, as the PB use at least 5 internally! So there
could have some problems here...	

>>  Definitely NO. Because the structure of them isn't the same at all. PB
>>  one is much more complex.
>
>But of course the PB one is better. Will it be possible to make your own 
>libraries, like with Blitz?

	Yes, of course. But it will be to be 100 % in assembler, like Blitz 2.
The only waranty to have optimized libs :-)

		Good bye,

                        Fred.

