@NODE "Mail_560" "PUNCH-SE and Interleaved bitmaps"
Date: Fri, 11 Jun 1999 03:35:45 +0100 (BST)
From: Wiremu TeKani <tekani@yahoo.com>
Subject: PUNCH-SE and Interleaved bitmaps
Encoding: 8bit
X-UIDL: 652bc67bc52907e801550237486c1a8e

Me wrote:
>> I'm back to work on PUNCH-Special Edition. I'm using Manfred Linzners
>> CPU-Blitter routine because this game uses about 600-700K in Bobs and
>> I want this thing to work inside an A500 1/2Meg CHIP 1/2Meg FAST. Its
>> former incarnation, "PUNCH!" was written in AM*S in '94 and only used
>> about 200K (Suprise suprise). Yes, I realise it's sheer madness.
 
And Anton Reinhauer wrote:
>   I assume it's in Blitz mode- have you got interleaved bitmaps, so your
> blits don't hold up the CPU- I assume they'll work with HAM.

Yup, it IS in Blitz mode.  Here's the 'sheer madness' part.  PUNCH-SE V1.0 is
in HAM mode.  The amount of memory it needs to work is huge from an A500 half
CHIP half FAST standpoint, and although I wanted to use interleaved bitmaps I
came up with a bizarre compromise:

Each of the two characters (In the Jpeg attachment) are actually 4 BITPLANES
deep, but each SHAPE contains its own pallette to make best use of each shape.

                   .---------------------------------.
                   |                 XXXXXXXXXXXXXXXX|
                   |                 XXXXXXXXXXXXXXXX|
                   |                 XXXXXXXXXXXXXXXX|
                   |                 XXXXXXXXXXXXXXXX|
                   |                 XXXXXXXXXXXXXXXX|
                   |                 XXXXXXXXXXXXXXXX|
                   |                 XXXXXXXXXXXXXXXX|
                   |                 XXXXXXXXXXXXXXXX|
                   |                 XXXXXXXXXXXXXXXX|
                   `---------------------------------'

The Coplist is 5 BITPLANES thick, but the program only draws to 4 of them.  The
5th BITPLANE has the side one characters on clear, the other side full, that
way each character has a 16 colour palette each. The places where they overlap
are  compensated for by Offset Qblits.  The actual screen size is about
256x140(?!)
the rest gets filled up with scoreboards and stuff.

Currently I can't figure how to do this with interleaved bitmaps without have a
huge redundant 5th bitplane.

Simple huh?

