Hello Ayar
     Hiya, Ayar... ,on 02-Jul-99 you mailed me about: Random Numbers! So I`ma reply`in...

[=> Hello;
[=>     I'm doing a ranking system to give the player an idea on how they've
[=> done. To assign the rank, I *cough* use an, er, random number *snigger*


[=> Anyway, I have the following line:
[=> 
[=> rank=Rnd(6)
[=> ;rank is byte
[=> 
[=> What values can this return?

0,1,2,3,4,5 or 6.

[=> Which of the returned values are more likely, and can anyone explain

None... Not if you randomize it first, try this:

RRandomize Timer

Rank.b=RRnd(0,6)
NPrint Rank

This will take the initial random-seed of the miggy`s CIATimer..
This is as "Random" as you`ll get it :) (I think)

[=> how my Miggy does random numbers? Surely computers are too stupid to

It`s just a mathematical formula, basically, it has an inital number, then
it performs a mathematical calculation on it to change it.. 
This means that if you use Rnd or RRnd without RRandomize, the inital
/Seed/ hasn`t changed, and everytime you run your program it will
pick the numbers in exactly the same order.

[=> pick a number out of a hat? (Not, literally, of course.)

Of course not. :)

