Content-Disposition: attachment; filename="ELECTRIC_english.txt"
Encoding: quoted-printable

 2. The description of the electrical basic circuit of the memory expansi=
on module=0D
=0D
=0D
=0D
=0D
=0D
 The development of the electrical basic circuit is reduced to realizatio=
n of separate blocks of a function chart, connections between blocks and =
additional connections ensuring work of elements in proper mode.=0D
=0D
=0D
=0D
 The drawing of the electrical basic circuit is given in the appendix (1 =
sheet =804) and on the poster (1 sheet =801).=0D
=0D
=0D
=0D
 The given circuit is constructed on the basis of the system bus of Amiga=
500, which includes the system bus of the microprocessor 68000 (described=
 above)=0D
and additional control signals. The following signals used as additional =
control signals:=0D
 =0D
=0D
* CDAC - this signal is rotated by 90 degrees (off 68000 frequency signal=
 =0D
 (CPUCLK), this means that the front of this signal is late off CPUCLK by=
 70 ns;=0D
=0D
* /OVR - when active, it cancels decoding of some address spaces in Amiga=
500 (it is used for PLA FX740LC68);=0D
=0D
 =0D
=0D
  This scheme starts working with reset (/RESET), which clears interrupt =
flag that was set at output of DD12.2 chip. Also RS-trigger, made with DD=
3.5,DD3.6,DD5.3,DD5.4 (=8A=901533=8B=8D1, =8A=901533=8B=881) chips, is se=
t, which leads to selecting system ROM at any address space until the fir=
st ROM select. This is necessary to get the reset vector located at $0000=
04  in ROM, not in RAM. =0D
=0D
=0D
=0D
The further necessary initialization of the necessary circuit's triggers =
occurs due to initial high (inactive) level on an input /AS after reset o=
f Amiga500. Then address decoding block becomes waiting for active low le=
vel of address getting signal (/AS).=0D
=0D
 =0D
=0D
=0D
=0D
Address decoding block is made of chips DD1, DD2.1, DD2.2=0D
=0D
(=8A=901533=88=847, =8A=901533=8B=881). =0D
=0D
=0D
=0D
  =0D
 DD1 decoder splits 16Mb address space into 8 parts of 2Mb=0D
=0D
=0D
$800000-$9FFFFF, $A00000-$BFFFFF, $C00000-$DFFFFF, $E00000-$FFFFFF. This =
helps to reduce the number of decoders in other parts of the scheme. Sign=
als of selecting the last two spaces come from output of DD1 chip to HD c=
ontroller and ROM control block. =0D
=0D
=0D
  Logical gates DD2.1 and DD2.2 join four address spaces $200000-$3FFFFF,=
 $400000-$5FFFFF, $600000-$7FFFFF, $800000-$9FFFFF in two=0D
$200000-$5FFFFF, $600000-$9FFFFF of 4Mb each, which are used by dynamic m=
emory controller.=0D
Fixable switcher, shown as KN1 at the scheme, when circuited, allows to s=
witch off=0D
decoding of all the address spaces by DD1; that turns off all the scheme =
blocks of=0D
Amiga500.=0D
=0D
=0D
=0D
 =0D
=0D
 =0D
 Harddisk controller is made with DD2.4, DD4.3, DD4.4, DD10-DD13=0D
=0D
(=8A=901533=8B=881, =8A=901533=8B=8B1, =8A=901533=88=847, =8A=901533=88=84=
14, =8A=901533=92=8C2, =8A=901533=8B=8F8) chips.=0D
=0D
=0D
=0D
  /C0 signal, which comes from address decoding block, goes to=0D
DD10 decoder, which gives 64kb of address space ($DA0000-$DAFFFF) from a =
range of 2=8Cb.=0D
 =0D
=0D
=0D
=0D
To make (/CS0 and /CS1) active while accessing harddrive ports you=0D
need narrower address space, and that is made by=0D
DD11.1 decoder and DD12.1 trigger (it holds /CS0 low in relation to =0D
/IOW and /IOR). /CS0 signal becomes active when accessing =0D
$DA2000-$DA2FFF address, and /CS1 - when acessing $DA3000-$DA3FFF. =0D
=0D
=0D
=0D
 /IOR and /IOW signals are made at the output of=0D
 DD11.2 decoder while reading or writing to $DA0000-$DA3FFF.=0D
 Signal of register writing (DD12.2 trigger) of interrupt flag goes from =
DD4.3 output. =0D
 This signal resets the trigger and deactivates the interrupt signal =0D
 /INT2, connected to the system bus of Amiga500.=0D
=0D
=0D
=0D
 Reading of interrupt flag register is made while output of DD4.4 is low.=
 Information=0D
 on interrupt flag is tranferred to the data bus through D15 line if read=
ing $DA9000-$DA9FFF addresses.=0D
 Interrupt flag is set if IRQ signal transerred from harddrive connector =
to the input=0D
 11 of DD12.2 trigger, is switched positive.=0D
=0D
=0D
 The =911 capacitor is used to remove errors from IRQ line. =0D
 IRQ signal is connected to the ground through R2 resistance to get a log=
ical 0=0D
 when harddrive is disconnected.=0D
=0D
=0D
=0D
 DD13.1 is used as a buffer with the third output condition, and avoids=0D=

 possible conflicts at data bus.=0D
=0D
=0D
 DD13.2 makes collector at /INT2 line open.=0D
=0D
=0D
=0D
 Dynamic memory controller is made with DD2.3,DD3.1-DD3.4,=0D
=0D
DD4.1,DD4.2,DD5.1,DD5.2,DD6-DD9,DD13.1 (=8A=901533=8B=881, =8A=901533=8B=8D=
1, =8A=901533=8B=8B1,=0D
=0D
=8A=901533=92=8C2, =8A=901533=8B=8F8, =8A=901533=88=8414) chips.=0D
=0D
=0D
=0D
 The contoller gets two signals from address decoding block=0D
 which are used by DD2.3 for making the /RAMSEL signal, used for =0D
 selecting address space of 8Mb ($200000-$9FFFFF) of the memory. The=0D
 DD6.1 trigger makes =0D
 /RAMSEL signal latch at the trird processor clock using the next=0D
 negative switching. It allows to get (/RASC) signal at this trigger's ou=
tput=0D
 from the middle of the third cycle of =8C=9168000 to the end of /AS sign=
al.=0D
=0D
=0D
=0D
  The /RASC signal takes part in forming signals that are responsible for=
 selecting rows=0D
in dynamic memory module. The middle of =8C=9168000's third cycle is a be=
ginning of dynamic memory reading/writing cycle. =0D
=0D
  DD3.3-DD3.4, DD13.3 chips allow to form the =0D
ADR_SW signal. It happens due to /RASC signal delay, which is necessary f=
or=0D
address switching front's delaying in multiplexers block off row selectio=
n signals=0D
(/RAS1, /RAS0). Next CDAC front (positive) latches the low level at DD6.2=
 trigger.=0D
This results in forming /RASC signal at the output of this trigger, which=
=0D
longs from the beginning of the fourth cycle to the end of /AS signal=0D
(the end of sixth cycle).=0D
=0D
The /CASC signal takes part in forming /CAS0, /CAS1, /CAS2 =A8 /CAS3 sign=
als,=0D
which are used for dynamic memory's row selection. =0D
=0D
 This scheme uses "0 wait states" type of memory regeneration=0D
(without CPU waiting cycles; this makes memory speed not less than 70ns).=
=0D
 It needs constant regenration with cycles' frequency equal to frequency=0D=

of REGCLK signal, which comes from the high bit of DD20 counter.=0D
=0D
  This counter divides =85 frequency by 128. When the counter gets 1 in t=
he high bit=0D
(REGCLK),  this 1 latches in DD7.1 trigger with negative CDAC signal swit=
ching=0D
(7MHz frequency). Trigger's direct output gets signal switching from low =
to high.=0D
This output is connected to the input of DD20 counter's reset.=0D
When this input gets a high level voltage, the counter resets to zero.=0D=

=0D
  The inverse output of DD7.1 forms a single negative impulse one CPU cyc=
le long=0D
(140ns), which activates all /CAS signals through DD9 chip, beginning dyn=
amic memory regeneration.=0D
When coming through DD7.2 trigger, this signal lags by the half of the CP=
U cycle,=0D
and the resulting signal activates all the /RAS signals using DD5.1 and D=
D5.2.=0D
That ensures /CAS regeneration before /RAS. The regeneration is made whil=
e there's =0D
no active low /AS signal, i.e. =E2=AE between memory access cycles. =0D
=0D
  The memory block has 32 data lines in four groups by 8 bit, =0D
with every group activated by its own /CAS signal. This allows pairwise j=
oining=0D
of the lines=8F=AE=ED=E2=AE=AC=E3 to the one 16-bit one. DD8 decoder shou=
ld activate the correspondong=0D
/CAS signal pairs. /UDS and /LDS signals that come to DD8's input ensure =
reading/writing=0D
high or low data byte of the 16-bit bus or its simultaneous output. See d=
etails=0D
in the table 2.1.=0D
 =0D
 =0D
 Table 2.1=0D
=0D
  Memory selection signals' distribution=0D
=0D
-----------------------------------------=0D
|  $800000-$9FFFFF  |  $400000-$5FFFFF  |=0D
-----------------------------------------=0D
| /UDS    | /LDS    | /UDS    | /LDS    |=0D
|---------|---------|---------|---------|=0D
| /RAS1   | /RAS1   | /RAS0   | /RAS0   |=0D
| /CAS3   | /CAS2   | /CAS3   | /CAS2   |=0D
| D31-D24 | D23-D16 | D31-D24 | D23-D16 |=0D
-----------------------------------------=0D
=0D
-----------------------------------------=0D
|  $600000-$7FFFFF  |  $200000-$3FFFFF  |=0D
-----------------------------------------=0D
| /UDS    | /LDS    | /UDS    | /LDS    |=0D
|---------|---------|---------|---------|=0D
| /RAS1   | /RAS1   | /RAS0   | /RAS0   |=0D
| /CAS1   | /CAS0   | /CAS1   | /CAS0   |=0D
| D15-D08 | D07-D00 | D15-D08 | D07-D00 |=0D
-----------------------------------------=0D
=0D
  DD16-DD18 chips ensure multiplexing of the addresses of the system addr=
ess bus=0D
using ADR_SW signal, which is active between /RAS and /CAS signals.=0D
When ADR_SW is high, dynamic memory row address is latched by =0D
the negative front of /RAS signal; When ADR_SW is low, dynamic memory=0D
column address is latched by the negative front of /CAS signal.=0D
=0D
  R3-R18 resistors ensure electrical coordination of multiplexers' output=
s=0D
with dynamic memory module inputs.=0D
=0D
 =0D
  ROM control block is made with DD13.3(=8A=901533=8B=8D1, =8A=901533=8B=88=
1,=0D
=8A=901533=8B=8F8) chips.=0D
=0D
  RS-trigger, made of DD3.5,DD3.6,DD5.3,DD5.4 (=8A=901533=8B=8D1, =8A=901=
533=8B=881),=0D
after reset forms the signal to select a reset vector from location $0000=
04=0D
of the system ROM, not the chip RAM of Amiga500. Therefore =0D
DD13.3 gets switched to the third mode. /ROM_OE output gets then attracte=
d through=0D
the resistor to the common output, to select a CPU reset vector, which ho=
lds=0D
the first command's address. Command's address is located at the ROM addr=
ess space=0D
to make /=850 signal by the address decoding block within the next =0D
memory reading cycle. This signal ensures switching RS-trigger to operati=
on mode,=0D
when DD13.3 switches its /ROM_OE output from the third mode to /=850 sign=
al passing mode.=0D
=0D
  /ROM_OE signal goes to the 'permit data transfer' input of =0D
DD14-DD15 chips' bus. Chip select input is connected to the ground to =0D=

ensure permanent data address selecting to the end of the sixth CPU cycle=
=2E=0D
=801-=8018 signals are used to select the data inside an address space of=
 512Kb.=0D
There is no =800 signal in =8C=9168000, so it's replaced by /UDS and /LDS=
 signals when writing.=0D
There's no need to use these signals when reading, as the =8C=9168000 lat=
ches=0D
the needed data from the data bus in the end of the sixth cycle. This all=
ows to connect=0D
two 8-bit ROM chips to 16-bit data bus and to select them both even if CP=
U needs=0D
to read 1 byte of data.=0D
=0D
  When reading ROM DD14 chip outputs the even (high) data byte D15-D8,=0D=

and the DD15 chip gives the odd (low) data byte D7-D0. Contents of ROM ch=
ips has to be=0D
split into odd and even part.=0D
=0D
 =0D
  This scheme uses power supply of +5V transferred through the system con=
nector of=0D
Amiga500, shown as =951 at the scheme. The ground bus is taken of the sam=
e connector=0D
of 11 pins, uniformly distributed on the connector. It is used to reduce =
noise=0D
at the ground bus. That is why ground bus is located next to +5V line, an=
d they both=0D
are wider that other signal conductors. =913-=9114 capacitors are located=
 near the chips'=0D
power output to avoid local noise on these chips. +12V suuply is not used=
 by the =0D
scheme, but it is needed for HDD to work. =0D
 =


--BOUNDARY.1748377944.1

