@NODE "Mail_584" "Re: Screen Events"
From: "David McMinn" <D.Mcminn@eee.rgu.ac.uk>
Organization: The Robert Gordon University, E&EE
Date: Fri, 2 Jul 1999 16:24:56 +0100
Subject: Re: Screen Events
Encoding: 8bit
X-UIDL: 16a18c7a97a5b0741244aea1ea7cc557


> QBlit and BBlit use the same collision commands, so they are equal in this
> dept. I'm not having problems with it. I just don't understand how Blitz
> differentiates between two shapes on the screen when you test for
> collisions. Say:
> 
> You have two shapes on screen, both with the ID of 1 (i.e. LoadShape
> 1,"blahblah.iff")
> 
> Then you get shapeshit which detects collisions between shapes. How
> does it know which shape to test? AM*S uses a unique ID for each
> sprite/bob on screen, so is easy.
> 
> The ShapesHit command has X and Y params, yet I can't see how they
> work.

Right. There are two sets of Shape# , X, Y parameters. Right? You have the x 
and y co-ordinates and the shape number for all the shapes you have on the 
screen. Right?

like:

player1x = 50
player1y = 10
and you are using shape #1 for player 1

similaryly:

player2x = 100
player2y = 64
and you are also using shape #1 for player 2

You do this:

blit 1,player1x,player1y
blit 1,player2x,player2y

if ShapesHit(1,player1x,play1y,1,player2x,player2y) then goto 
playermustdiehorriblywithbloodandgutsspewingeverywhere

(that last one should all be one line ;)



Each shape blitz loads contains information about it (duh;):

width, height, xhandle, yhandle (the handles specify which pixel of the shape 
gets bitted at the position you specify in the blit commands), cookiecut and 
the actual shape data. When you do shapeshit, blitz uses the cookiecut (which 
is a mask of all the pixels that the shape actually uses i.e. not colour 0) to 
determine if the two shapes overlap. A simple example I can be arsed 
illustrating just checks the rectangular area around the shape:

Function.w myshitshape{shape1.w, x1.w, y1.w, shape2.w, x2.w, y2.w}
if(x1-shape1\xhandle)<(x2-shape2\xhandle+shape2\width) Then Function Return -1
if(x1-shape1\xhandle+shape1\width)>(x2-shape2\xhandle) Then Function Return -1
if(y1-shape1\yhandle)<(y2-shape2\yhandle+shape2\height) Then Function Return -1
if(y1-shape1\yhandle+shape1\height)>(y2-shape2\yhandle) Then Function Return -1
Function Return 0
End Function

So if any of the edges of the shapes overlap then you get a hit returned. The 
same shape number can be used because the shapes do not store the data about 
where they are bitted, only about their dimensions. You provide (and store) the 
x and y co-ordinates, which is why you also pass them to the shapeshit command.

> Sam Brookes did do summat here, but to be honest, I didn't understand it
> :) Sorry Sam if u're still on te list :)

Didn't he run up a huge phone bill and have to leave the internet?

