> You have two shapes on screen, both with the ID of 1
> (i.e. LoadShape
> 1,"blahblah.iff")
> 
> Then you get shapeshit which detects collisions
> between shapes. How
> does it know which shape to test? AM*S uses a unique
> ID for each
> sprite/bob on screen, so is easy.

This is what I didn't want to be patronising about- when you blit a
shape, it becomes part of the bitmap, there is no object on the screen
you can identify. You should have x,y and 'shape' variables for each
object in the game (the player, a bullet etc.). The shape parameter
does not identify the object, but refers to the shape that should be
blitted for it. For the shapeshit command you may type:

If ShapesHit player\frame,player\x,player\y,
enemy(1)\frame,enemy(1)\x,enemy(1)\y

It gets the smallest rectangles that cover the shapes, puts them at the
x and y values given, and checks for an overlap. If you think of the
maths involved, this is quite slow.

> The ShapesHit command has X and Y params, yet I
> can't see how they
> work.

Ahhhhhh!

