@NODE "Mail_587" "Re: Screen Events"
From: Curt Esser <camge@ix.netcom.com>
Date: Fri, 02 Jul 1999 16:21:15 -0500
Subject: Re: Screen Events
X-UIDL: fb727827eaf3a1fb38910a7bcd9d4f13

Hi Gaz-JD/FX-s^D

On 01-Jul-99, Gaz-JD/FX-s^D wrote:

> PQ: Can't help you there, sorry. I always use BBlit. That would be
> PQ: the.. er, ShapesHit command? All the collision commands seem slow.
> PQ: Are you having problems with it, or do you just not understand? (I
> PQ: don't want to patronise you!)
> 
> QBlit and BBlit use the same collision commands, so they are equal in
> this dept. I'm not having problems with it. I just don't understand
> how Blitz differentiates between two shapes on the screen when you
> test for collisions. Say:
> 
> You have two shapes on screen, both with the ID of 1 (i.e. LoadShape
> 1,"blahblah.iff")
> 
> Then you get shapeshit which detects collisions between shapes. How
> does it know which shape to test? AM*S uses a unique ID for each
> sprite/bob on screen, so is easy.

It's really NOT testing the shapes at all but simply checks to see if the
two rectangles the given shapes WOULD occupy IF they were Blitted at the
specified co-ordinates would overlap each other. 

There is no actual collision detecting. You don't even need to Blit the
shapes at all...  You can check BEFORE blitting, and draw an explosion or
something instead if need be...
> 
> The ShapesHit command has X and Y params, yet I can't see how they
> work.

These are the locations the shapes will (or have) been blitted to.  It's
really nothing more than a deluxe version of the RectsHit command - it
automatically gets the size and handle offset of the two rectangles from
the specified shapes.

