@NODE "Mail_601" "Re: Shapes (Identification, and some other stuff)"
 for scott@online.u-net.com; Tue, 1 Jun 1999 12:13:22 +0000
From: Curt Esser <camge@ix.netcom.com>
Date: Tue, 01 Jun 1999 06:05:28 -0500
Subject: Re: Shapes (Identification, and some other stuff)

Hi Rob

On 31-May-99, Rob Hutchinson wrote:
> Hello,
> 
>   Does anyone know anything about Blitz`s "Shapes" format?..

A little bit...
 
> Specifically a way to identify a file (a byte-run).. And a way to
> tell how many shapes are in the file..?

OK, first, this applies strictly to the standard Blitz shapes file, I don't
know about the RI shapes file.

The shapes file itself looks to be nothing more than a memory dump of each
Shape newtype, followed by a memory dump of the graphic data (except for
the cookie - which is remade when a shape file is loaded)

If there is more than one shape, the next Shape newtype and graphic data
follows immediately.

There is no "header" at all, AFAIK, so I don't really see a way to ID a file
as a Blitz shapes file, although I could be wrong about that.


Anyway, all the pertinant info about each shape is found in the 32 byte
"chunk" (newtype) preceeding each shape, the width, height, depth, handle
info, etc...
Set up just the same as the newtype - of course, the memory pointers are
meaningless but all the rest can be read and used for whatever...

To tell how many shapes are in the file, you would read the first chunk.  At
byte 26 is a word (corresponds to allbpmem in the NewType) which gives the
length, in bytes, of the graphic data.

So, to find the start of the next shape, you skip ahead this many bytes
AFTER THE 32 byte chunk.

If you don't hit the end of the file, you can repeat this to find the next
shape.   
                                    Yours electronically,
                                    Curt Esser
                                    camge@ix.netcom.com
                                    http://members.xoom.com/Curt_Esser/



