Subject: Stack sizes when running from editor

--Message-Boundary-9330
encoding: Quoted-printable
Content-description: Mail message body

Your program inherits the same stack size (not the same stack) as the Blit=
z2 
program. So there is no need to go ape and create some mad stack changing =
code 
(although it was definately worth the effort Rob :), just change the stack=
 size 
in the Blitz2 program icon (not TEd) and run it from the icon, or using a =
CLI 
window, set the stack size then run blitz2. If you run it from the Execute=
 
Command menu item, you will get a stack of 4096 bytes.

Proved by the attached program (unless it is wrong - tell me if it is).


-- 
|) /\ \/ ][ |)   |\/| =A9 |\/| ][ |\| |\|
 dmcminn@house-of-mojo.freeserve.co.uk
  http://members.xoom.com/David_McMinn
             ICQ=3D16827694
I am Pentium of Borg, division is futile -
you will be approximated



--Message-Boundary-9330
encoding: 7BIT
Content-description: Text from file 'stacksize.bb2'

; Description:      Find out size of current stack
;
; Type:             SYSTEM
;
; Last updated:     3rd June
;
; Author:           David McMinn
;
; Requires:         amigalibs.res

; Find the pointer to our task
*t.Task = FindTask_(0)

; Print the difference between the upper and lower addresses
; of our stack (which would be the size of our stack :)
NPrint *t\tc_SPUpper - *t\tc_SPLower

; Wait a short time and then quit
Delay_ 150
End



--Message-Boundary-9330

