@NODE "Mail_639" "Re: Text Readers (WAS Re: My new BUM)"
From: "Linda Bell" <zalda@home4968.freeserve.co.uk>
Subject: Re: Text Readers (WAS Re: My new BUM)
Date: Sun, 6 Jun 1999 13:38:37 +0100
X-UIDL: 5ca346ec2e2187f70cb0f5d1b55e3088


Alright, I`ll come clean.

I didn`t like MUI when I first saw it about 3-4 years ago, because I didn`t
like the millions of files it uses.  I like to know what everything on my
hard drive is for - and don`t like having stuff left on there after
uninstalling something that I later decide I don`t like.

Yes I only have an 030.

But the main reason is that I`ve only got 346k free on my Work partition -
yes 346k free - however, I`ve just towered my Amiga so that I can get a big
3.5inch HD, and I`ve just archived everything to floppy in preparation for
this.  The main reason I would have to have MUI is for DrawStudio - which I
didn`t buy when it came out - for the simple reason that it uses MUI - I
doubt it is still available.

Furthermore - I don`t care about cosmetics - my Amiga is for running
applications - I don`t care whether I can see through the icons that I click
on - I`m not trying to impress casual PC observers.  I launch everything
from ToolsDaemon, and therefore never see my icons.  And who cares whether
buttons have got nice little patterns on them - as long as they`ve got text
that describes what they do when you push them.  I`ll stop here because I
could go on forever.

I will give MUI another chance when I get a bigger HD and then let you knnow
whether I`ve fallen in love or not.  In the meantime, lets not annoy those
who are not interested in this thread by replying back and forth.  Naturally
those of you that use it have far more experience of it than I do, and are
better able to judge its merits - one thing I hate about bragging PC owners
is the fact that Windows is generally all they know - but they still feel
able to comment on the Amiga - so I apologize.  But state again that I feel
it is largely cosmetic.

VIC





