@NODE "Mail_645" "Re: Text Readers (WAS Re: My new BUM)"
From: Mikkel =?iso-8859-1?Q?L=F8kke?= <flameduck@software.dk>
Date: Mon, 07 Jun 1999 13:20:10 +0200
Organization: M2 productions
Subject: Re: Text Readers (WAS Re: My new BUM)
Encoding: 8bit
X-UIDL: f73d686d9f6917f5347b6bbb46140b3b

Hello Daniel.

You wrote:

>> Yes I only have an 030.

> Well upgrade!!

>> But the main reason is that I`ve only got 346k free on my Work partition -
>> yes 346k free - however, I`ve just towered my Amiga so that I can get a
>> big 3.5inch HD, and I`ve just archived everything to floppy in preparation
>> for this. The main reason I would have to have MUI is for DrawStudio -
>> which I didn`t buy when it came out - for the simple reason that it uses
>> MUI - I doubt it is still available.

> Well that is just your stupid fault.....not using one of the best programs
> on the Amiga because it uses MUI is total stupidity.

> As for your 346k of space left, that your fault again for not upgrading. You
> shouldn't expect people to program for crappy Gadtools when something like
> MUI is available.

Daniel, you seem to be under the impression that hardware should adapt to the demands of software, not the other way arround, a misconception often carried by PC-owners. (Not implying that you are one, just stating the facts). Surely you must understand that not everyone can fork over enough dough to buy a CyberStorm PPC, and a 9GB WideSCSI Harddrive. You must try to be  little more reasonble and understanding.

> But, again, it's your choice if you want to miss out on some of the best
> software written for the amiga that otherwise wouldn't exist without MUI.

Software creators have since the dawn of time written "custom" GUI objects, even if a certain OS had perfectly good ways of doing the same thing. I'm not going to argue that MUI's are easy to create because firstly I havn't tried it, and secondly I don't really care either. I use MUI, by force rather than choice, and suffer under the instabilities that come with it. Certainly this is not "only" MUI's fault, it's just as much the OS, and possibly the appliction programmers that havn't quite understood the way MUI works (It's so easy, you might miss something [?]). Anyway MUI is the cause of much frustration, esp. when one has worked with Linux and Enlightenment, the way MUI handles things is downright sad.


Greets,
-- 

