@NODE "Mail_722" "Vblank timer and Ticks GFX card test"
From: Anton Reinauer <anton@ww.co.nz>
Date: Fri, 25 Jun 1999 14:14:18 +1200
Subject: Vblank timer and Ticks GFX card test
X-UIDL: 0050e3ffd5b279fc83a263ccc1d03a9c

--BOUNDARY.2017473568.1

Yo, Stephen Lebed and others with GFX cards :)

  Okaley-dokaley here's a little test program to see if the the Ticks,
and/or Vblank timer run the same under PAL/NTSC, as under a Graphics
card screen with a different screen rate.
  I'm using a CIA timer to do an accurate time interval which /won't/
change under a Graphics card screen.
  It prints out what I get under PAL here (around 3,026 Ticks/Vblanks in
about one minute). You might get a slight varience of 3,027 or 3,028 at
most. Note: at the time, the only program using any CPU time was this
test program! 

   Can as many people as possible with Graphics cards test it please-
run it in the Blitz editor- it will bring up the standard Blitz Cli
window on Workbench, so your WB will need to be running on a GFX card.
Can you give the results back with the screenmode it was running in and
speed the screen was running at (ie: 85hz etc). Can you also test at
different resolutions and frame rates please :-)

  This way we can sort this out for good :-)  AFAIK, the GFX card screen
shouldn't affect Ticks or the Vblank, as I'm sure Ticks runs off the
EClock (either PAL or NTSC rates), and the VBlank timer runs off one of
the CIA chips (again either PAl or NTSC).
  Also can someone with NTSC tell me what results they get, also those
with GFX cards would be appreciated- ta :-) 

  If my theory is correct, we should be able to use the Vblank timer for
an accurate long term timer, I'd just have to add a routine to check
wether the machine was running in PAL or NTSC and drop or add frames
according to wether your game is meant to originally run on PAL or
NTSC. Also you'd have to check each frame that the user hadn't switched
from PAL to NTSC (or vice-versa), in the middle of your game) ; this
again could be handled transparently, even if they switched back
between the two modes many times!  

    Seeya- Anton
-- 
        Anton Reinauer <anton@ww.co.nz>
      A500,DF1:,0.5MC,8.5MF,60HDD,WB3.1 &1.3/2.0 
    A1200,2M,CD-Rom,25/040,200/PPC ,WB3.0 
          
    Project: UDP_Chat [99%]- an Internet multi-player code, test-bed 
      for my game Pyro-Mid. - Aminet: dev/basic/UDP_Chat.lha (V2.5)
         <http://www.ww.co.nz/home/anton/>


