@ENDNODE
@NODE "Mail_749" "Re: We're on a collision course..."
From: "Linda Bell" <zalda@home4968.freeserve.co.uk>
        "Samuel Brookes" <ami-gerbil@ami-gerbil.freeserve.co.uk>
Subject: Re: We're on a collision course...
Date: Sat, 12 Jun 1999 19:33:25 +0100
X-UIDL: d018718a90d4af48b3888937bccbbe20

There is another way to detect collision that I use.  What you can do, is
change the HANDLE for the players car to the bottom right hand corner, but
leave all the other graphics the same - that way you can

IF PlayerX>ComX
    IF PlayerX<ComX+#ComXWidth
        IF PlayerY>ComY
            IF PlayerY<ComY+#ComYWidth
                THEN shapes have collided.
            ENDIF
        ENDIF
ENDIF

This way, you don`t need to pass all of the co-ordinates to a routine, and
it will exit as soon as a condition isn`t met.  Also, #ComX/YWidth will
probably be constants, so no need to load registers with variables.  And the
best part about this routine, is you can test for areas smaller than the
shapes, for when you have shapes that have got fiddly little bits sticking
out, that won`t look as though they collided to the player.

Don`t know if this is faster than using ShapesHit - though you do have to
pass everything to that routine, but it is also more flexible.

I used this method for George 2.

VIC




